ysis of fear and inaction. Ilan Rubin's drumming immediately distinguishes it from previous AVA — more muscular and precise.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo raw alternative rock, 104 BPM, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin co-production, sleep-paralysis and metaphorical-paralysis lyric, rawer more muscular than Love era, Dream Walker Poet Anderson concept, promotional single energy, under 4:30", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo raw rock song about paralysis — both the literal experience of being unable to move in a dream state and the metaphorical paralysis of being frozen by fear or indecision. The narrator is trying to break free from a state that holds them. Under 4:30."}, {"title": "The Wolfpack", "album": "The Dream Walker", "year": 2014, "bpm": 120, "vibe": "First single · community of searchers · collective identity within the dream", "dna": "First single from The Dream Walker, released Halloween 2014. The wolfpack: a collective identity, a community that moves together, that finds safety and power in numbers. Within the Poet Anderson dream concept, the wolfpack represents the community of dream walkers. Music video released November 14, 2014.", "style_prompt": "Raw alternative rock single, 120 BPM, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin production, wolfpack-community lyric, collective-identity theme, Dream Walker concept, direct and raw compared to Love era, under 4:15", "lyric_prompt": "Write a raw alternative rock song about the wolfpack — a community of searchers who move together, find strength in collective identity, and navigate the uncertain landscape in formation. The wolfpack is both literal and metaphorical: a tribe of people who understand each other. Under 4:15."}, {"title": "Tunnels", "album": "The Dream Walker", "year": 2014, "bpm": 116, "vibe": "Second single · navigating the underground · tunnels as dream pathways", "dna": "Second single from The Dream Walker, released December 3, 2014. The tunnel as a dream symbol: the passage between states of consciousness, between waking and sleeping, between who you are and who you could be. The Poet Anderson concept uses the dream world as a literal navigable landscape.", "style_prompt": "Raw alternative rock, 116 BPM, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin Dream Walker production, tunnel-as-dream-pathway lyric, passage-between-states-of-consciousness, rawer and more direct than Love era, under 4:30", "lyric_prompt": "Write a raw rock song about tunnels — both literal underground passages and the dream-state tunnels between consciousness and the unknown. The narrator is moving through darkness toward something on the other side. The tunnel is both frightening and necessary. Under 4:30."}, {"title": "Kiss with a Spell", "album": "The Dream Walker", "year": 2014, "bpm": 110, "vibe": "Enchantment and magic of love · fairy tale register within dream concept", "dna": "110 BPM. The kiss with a spell: love as enchantment, as magic, as something that changes reality. Within the dream-concept album, the spell-kiss is a dream logic — the kind of transformation that only happens in sleep. A more romantic track within the Dream Walker's rawer sound.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo enchanted alternative rock, 110 BPM, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin Dream Walker production, spell-and-enchantment love lyric, fairy-tale magic within dream concept, rawer than Love era but romantically warmer, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo rock song about love as an enchantment — a kiss with a spell, a moment of magic that changes everything, that alters reality in the way only dreams can. The language pulls from fairy tale imagery within a rock framework. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Mercenaries", "album": "The Dream Walker", "year": 2014, "bpm": 118, "vibe": "Fighters for hire in the dream landscape · mercenaries as metaphor for willpower", "dna": "118 BPM. Within the Poet Anderson dream concept, mercenaries are those who fight for themselves in the dream landscape — hired warriors navigating a reality defined by their own will. A metaphor for self-determination and the fight to control your own narrative.", "style_prompt": "Driving raw alternative rock, 118 BPM, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin Dream Walker production, mercenaries-as-self-determination lyric, fighting-for-your-own-narrative theme, rawer more muscular than Love era, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a driving raw rock song about mercenaries — fighters who answer to no authority but their own will, who navigate any landscape by their own code. Within a dream concept, mercenaries are the dreamers who refuse to be controlled by anyone else's reality. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Bullets in the Wind", "album": "The Dream Walker", "year": 2014, "bpm": 113, "vibe": "Third single · bullets as futile weapons · words as weapons · dream ephemera", "dna": "Third single from The Dream Walker. Bullets in the wind: actions and words that are pointless in certain contexts, that simply blow away without effect. The futility of certain kinds of force. Within the dream concept, bullets don't stop what needs to happen.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo raw alternative rock, 113 BPM, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin Dream Walker production, bullets-in-wind futility lyric, ineffectiveness of force in certain contexts, rawer than Love era, under 4:20", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo raw rock song about the futility of bullets in the wind — actions, words, or force that simply disperse without effect because you cannot fight certain things that way. The narrator has realized that some battles require something other than weapons. Under 4:20."}, {"title": "The Disease", "album": "The Dream Walker", "year": 2014, "bpm": 122, "vibe": "Love as disease · consuming and spreading · Dream Walker faster track", "dna": "122 BPM. Love or obsession as a disease: it spreads, consumes, alters the host. The darker register of love within the Dream Walker concept. A more aggressive track within the album.", "style_prompt": "Raw driving alternative rock, 122 BPM, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin production, love-as-disease lyric, consuming-and-spreading obsession, darker register within Dream Walker, rawer and more aggressive, under 4:15", "lyric_prompt": "Write a raw driving rock song about love or obsession as a disease — something that spreads, consumes, and alters everything it touches. The narrator is infected and doesn't know whether to fight it or give in. Under 4:15."}, {"title": "Tremors", "album": "The Dream Walker", "year": 2014, "bpm": 118, "vibe": "Aftershocks of love and loss · tremors as residual feeling", "dna": "118 BPM. Tremors: the aftershocks that follow a major event. After love, after loss, after a seismic change in your life — the tremors continue. You feel them long after the main event. One of the Dream Walker's more emotionally resonant deep cuts.", "style_prompt": "Driving atmospheric alternative rock, 118 BPM, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin Dream Walker production, tremors-as-aftershock lyric, residual-feeling-after-major-event theme, emotional weight within rawer production, under 4:20", "lyric_prompt": "Write a driving rock song about tremors — the aftershocks that continue long after a major seismic event in your life. After love ends, after loss, after a fundamental change, you keep feeling the tremors. The ground has shifted and keeps shifting. Under 4:20."}, {"title": "Anomaly", "album": "The Dream Walker", "year": 2014, "bpm": 110, "vibe": "Dream Walker closer · the anomaly in the system · the unexplained element", "dna": "110 BPM. Closes The Dream Walker. The anomaly: the thing that doesn't fit the system, that breaks the model, that cannot be explained by existing frameworks. Within the Poet Anderson concept, the dream walker is an anomaly in waking reality. DeLonge's persistent interest in the unexplained — UFOs, consciousness, the things science can't yet explain.", "style_prompt": "Closing atmospheric alternative rock, 110 BPM, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin Dream Walker closing track, anomaly-as-the-unexplained lyric, dream-walker-as-impossible-element, DeLonge's interest in UFOs and consciousness, album-closing resolution of Poet Anderson concept", "lyric_prompt": "Write a closing rock song about being the anomaly — the element that doesn't fit any existing model, the thing that cannot be explained by current frameworks, the dream walker who doesn't belong to waking reality alone. The narrator accepts and embraces their status as the unexplained element. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Timebomb", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 135, "vibe": "Lifeforms opener · Brad Delson co-production · brighter more guitar-forward sound · explosive opener", "dna": "Opens Lifeforms — the 2021 album co-produced with Brad Delson of Linkin Park. A significant shift back toward brighter, more guitar-driven alternative rock. Kerrang! described the album as containing 'some of the band's best work, with Tom in particular sounding invigorated and on fine form.' The timebomb metaphor: love or life as something that will inevitably explode.", "style_prompt": "Bright driving alternative rock, 135 BPM, Brad Delson and DeLonge Lifeforms co-production, brighter more guitar-forward than Love era, timebomb-as-inevitable-explosion metaphor, DeLonge sounding invigorated Kerrang! noted, explosive opener energy, Rise Records 2021", "lyric_prompt": "Write a bright, driving alternative rock opener about a timebomb — love or life as something built to explode, an inevitable detonation you can feel counting down. The narrator knows the explosion is coming and is choosing to stand there anyway. Brighter and more guitar-forward than previous AVA albums. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Euphoria", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 90, "vibe": "State of pure joy · euphoria as destination · one of Lifeforms' standout tracks", "dna": "90 BPM. Official music video released. Euphoria as a destination and a state of being: the pure joy of love and existence. One of the Lifeforms tracks with an official video, indicating its status as a standout. The Brad Delson production gives it a more polished radio quality than the Dream Walker era.", "style_prompt": "Atmospheric euphoric alternative rock, 90 BPM, Brad Delson and DeLonge Lifeforms production, pure-joy-as-destination lyric, euphoria as a state of being, official music video track, polished radio quality within AVA framework, wide reverb guitars", "lyric_prompt": "Write an atmospheric rock song about euphoria as a destination — the state of pure joy that love produces, the feeling of having arrived somewhere extraordinary. The narrator has found the thing they were searching for and the result is overwhelming happiness. Under 4:25."}, {"title": "Spellbound", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 92, "vibe": "Enchantment and being bound by love · official music video · Lifeforms standout", "dna": "92 BPM. Official music video released. Being spellbound: completely enchanted and unable to break free. A classic AVA love concept — being bound to someone by something inexplicable. The Lifeforms production gives it more punch than the Love era equivalents.", "style_prompt": "Atmospheric enchanted alternative rock, 92 BPM, Brad Delson and DeLonge Lifeforms production, spellbound-by-love lyric, inexplicable enchantment theme, official video track, more punch than Love era, wide reverb, under 4:20", "lyric_prompt": "Write an atmospheric rock song about being completely spellbound — enchanted and unable to break free, held by something inexplicable. The narrator is not fighting it. Being spellbound is the most alive they've ever felt. Under 4:20."}, {"title": "No More Guns", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 92, "vibe": "Anti-violence statement · 2:40 shortest Lifeforms track · direct message", "dna": "92 BPM, 2:40 runtime — shortest Lifeforms track. Direct, unambiguous anti-violence message. DeLonge addressing gun violence with characteristic bluntness. The brevity matches the directness.", "style_prompt": "Direct short anti-violence alternative rock, 92 BPM, 2:40 max, DeLonge direct vocal, no-more-guns anti-violence message, Lifeforms Delson production, brevity and directness within AVA framework, under 2:45", "lyric_prompt": "Write a short, direct rock song with an unambiguous anti-violence message — no more guns. The narrator is done with the euphemism and the debate: no more guns. Under 2:45."}, {"title": "Losing My Mind", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 113, "vibe": "Love as madness · official music video · going beautifully insane", "dna": "113 BPM. Official music video released. Love as the thing that makes you lose your mind — in the best possible way. The beautiful madness of overwhelming feeling. One of the Lifeforms' more melodically accessible tracks.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo melodic alternative rock, 113 BPM, Brad Delson and DeLonge Lifeforms production, love-as-beautiful-madness lyric, losing-your-mind-for-love theme, melodically accessible official video track, under 3:55", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo melodic rock song about going beautifully insane because of love — losing your mind in the best possible way. The narrator is fully aware they are not thinking rationally and is completely at peace with it. Under 3:55."}, {"title": "Automatic", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 88, "vibe": "Love as automatic response · instinctive and involuntary · body over mind", "dna": "88 BPM. Love as automatic: a response you cannot control, an involuntary action. The body knows before the mind catches up. The Lifeforms production gives this a punchy, physical quality.", "style_prompt": "Atmospheric punchy alternative rock, 88 BPM, Brad Delson and DeLonge Lifeforms production, love-as-automatic-involuntary-response lyric, body-over-mind theme, punchy physical quality, under 3:25", "lyric_prompt": "Write an atmospheric rock song about love as an automatic response — involuntary, instinctive, happening before the mind can intervene. The narrator's body responds to this person before thought is possible. Under 3:25."}, {"title": "Restless Souls", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 110, "vibe": "Searching souls · always looking · Lifeforms visualizer track", "dna": "110 BPM. Visualizer released. Restless souls: the people who cannot settle, who are always searching for something more, who find peace only in movement and seeking. An AVA anthem for their particular fanbase — the searchers.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo searching atmospheric rock, 110 BPM, Brad Delson and DeLonge Lifeforms production, restless-souls-always-searching lyric, anthem for seekers, visualizer track, under 3:50", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo atmospheric rock song for the restless souls — the people who cannot settle, who are always searching for something more, who find peace only in movement and seeking. This is their anthem. Under 3:50."}, {"title": "Rebel Girl", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 125, "vibe": "Official music video · rebellious energy · female-addressed rock anthem", "dna": "125 BPM. Official music video released. Peaked at number 49 on Rock & Alternative Airplay. About a rebellious girl — a woman who doesn't conform, who defies expectations, who is irresistible precisely because of her refusal to be ordinary. One of Lifeforms' more energetic tracks.", "style_prompt": "Upbeat rebellious alternative rock, 125 BPM, Brad Delson and DeLonge Lifeforms production, rebel-girl lyric — woman who defies expectation, official video and charted single, Rock and Alternative Airplay, energetic within AVA framework", "lyric_prompt": "Write an upbeat rock song about a rebel girl — a woman who refuses to conform, who defies every expectation, who is completely herself regardless of what anyone wants her to be. The narrator is in awe of her refusal to be ordinary. Under 3:50."}, {"title": "A Fire in a Nameless Town", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 103, "vibe": "Anonymous catastrophe · somewhere specific and everywhere · fire as transformation", "dna": "103 BPM. The fire in a nameless town: a catastrophe that could be anywhere, that represents all catastrophes. The namelessness makes it universal. Fire as both destruction and transformation. One of the more literary Lifeforms titles.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo literary atmospheric rock, 103 BPM, Brad Delson and DeLonge Lifeforms production, universal-catastrophe-in-anonymous-location lyric, namelessness-makes-it-universal, fire-as-transformation, under 3:35", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo atmospheric rock song about a fire in a nameless town — a catastrophe that could be anywhere and therefore is everywhere, that represents every small crisis that goes unrecorded. The narrator witnesses something specific but universal. Under 3:35."}, {"title": "Kiss & Tell", "album": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "bpm": 85, "vibe": "Lifeforms closer · official music video · secret love made public · confession", "dna": "85 BPM. Official music video released. The phrase 'kiss and tell': confessing a secret love, making public what was private. Closes Lifeforms — and as the band's most recent studio album closer, functions as the current final word of the AVA catalog. DeLonge sounding invigorated per Kerrang!", "style_prompt": "Slow atmospheric closing alternative rock, 85 BPM, Brad Delson and DeLonge Lifeforms closing track, kiss-and-tell confession lyric, secret-made-public theme, official video album closer, DeLonge on fine form, current final word of AVA catalog, under 4:10", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow atmospheric closing rock song about kissing and telling — confessing a secret love, making public what has been private, the moment when you stop protecting something and let it be known. This is the last song on the most recent album: it should feel like a final honest confession. Under 4:10."}], "albums": [{"title": "We Don't Need to Whisper", "year": 2006, "style_prompt": "Vast cathedral-reverb space rock debut, Jeff Critter Newell production, 70–90 BPM slow tempo, DeLonge wide-vibrato tenor vocal, multiple reverb-drenched guitar layers, cinematic synthesizer pads, extended runtimes 4–7 minutes, post-punk meets atmospheric rock, Blink-182 hiatus context, San Diego 2006, went gold in US and Canada", "lyric_prompt": "Write a We Don't Need to Whisper-era AVA song: slow, vast, and completely earnest about love, humanity, and consciousness. The emotional world: a man who has left the world's biggest pop-punk band and is making the most important rock music ever made (his words). The lyric should be philosophical and grand without being cynical — DeLonge means every enormous word. Choose: love as the answer to war, the beauty of human potential, or the specific quality of someone who makes the world make sense. Extended runtime permitted. Under 6 minutes."}, {"title": "I-Empire", "year": 2007, "style_prompt": "Polished vast atmospheric rock, Jeff Critter Newell more refined than debut, 84–98 BPM, DeLonge wide-vibrato vocal at its most accessible, I-Empire individual-as-empire philosophy, everything's magic synth-rock energy, vast reverb but more radio-accessible, Matt Wachter bass addition, Geffen Records 2007", "lyric_prompt": "Write an I-Empire-era AVA song around the central philosophy of the individual as an empire: one person who contains multitudes, who can change the world, who is their own universe. The emotional world: a band making their case to the mainstream that these slow, vast, earnest songs are the most important thing happening in rock. Choose: the individual's power to transform reality through love, the magic that love casts over everything, or the call to other restless souls to wake up to their own potential. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Love / Love Part Two", "year": 2010, "style_prompt": "Self-produced cinematic space rock double album, DeLonge without Jeff Critter Newell, tied to William Eubank film Love, 70–154 BPM wide range, Valentine's Day 2010 free release most-downloaded-album-in-history, most ambitious AVA production, cosmos and love as unified subject, extended runtimes throughout", "lyric_prompt": "Write a Love-era AVA song in the spirit of the double album tied to a film about a solitary astronaut. The emotional world: love examined from every angle — cosmic, personal, mythological, philosophical — across an album released for free on Valentine's Day as a gift to the world. Choose: the Apollo mission as love metaphor, love as the only thing that survives any apocalypse, or the specific surrender to something larger than yourself. Extended runtime permitted. Under 6 minutes."}, {"title": "The Dream Walker", "year": 2014, "style_prompt": "Rawer alternative rock, DeLonge and Ilan Rubin duo production, no David Kennedy no Matt Wachter, Aaron Rubin co-producer, 104–128 BPM faster than Love era, Poet Anderson multimedia concept — dreams as navigable landscape, less reverb-heavy more direct, To The Stars Records", "lyric_prompt": "Write a Dream Walker-era AVA song within the Poet Anderson concept: a world where the dream landscape is navigable, where dream walkers move between sleeping and waking reality, where consciousness itself is a frontier. Rawer and more direct than the Love era. Choose: the tunnel between waking and dreaming, the wolfpack of like-minded dream explorers, or the anomaly who doesn't belong to ordinary reality. Under 4:30."}, {"title": "Lifeforms", "year": 2021, "style_prompt": "Invigorated guitar-forward alternative rock, Brad Delson co-production, brighter and punchier than Love era, 85–135 BPM range, Rise Records 2021, DeLonge post-UFO-disclosure-work energy, Kerrang! noted DeLonge on fine form, sci-fi alt-rock take, more immediate than Love era philosophy", "lyric_prompt": "Write a Lifeforms-era AVA song: DeLonge returning from years of UFO disclosure work and multimedia projects, sounding invigorated (Kerrang!) and making brighter more guitar-forward rock. The emotional world: love and existence examined through a sci-fi lens — life in all its forms, the universe as a living thing, the specific joy of being alive right now. More immediate and less slow-burn than the Love era. Choose: euphoria as a destination, the restless souls who keep searching, or the rebel who refuses every ordinary framework. Under 4:30."}]}, {"id": "avicii", "name": "Avicii", "genres": ["Progressive House", "EDM", "Dance-Pop", "Folk-EDM", "Melodic House"], "era": "2008–2018", "color": "#f5a623", "bio": "Tim Bergling (1989–2018), known as Avicii, was the Swedish DJ and producer who took electronic music to Top 40 radio. Self-taught from age 16, he built a sound that fused four-on-the-floor house beats with folk, country, gospel, and pop melody — a genre-defying hybrid that made him one of the most streamed artists of the 2010s. He was influenced equally by Eric Prydz and Daft Punk on the electronic side and by Etta James, Ray Charles, Mumford & Sons, and Of Monsters and Men on the melodic side. He died by suicide in April 2018, aged 28. All profits from his posthumous album TIM go to the Tim Bergling Foundation for mental health awareness. Three studio albums: True (2013), Stories (2015), TIM (2019).", "producer_notes": "Avicii self-produced all key material. Signature: euphoric four-on-the-floor kick drum, vocal chops or featured singers with emotional soul/folk qualities, ascending melodic synth leads, key changes in the final chorus for emotional lift. He sampled deeply from soul and gospel. Collaborators: Vargas & Lagola (key TIM era partners), Aloe Blacc (Wake Me Up, SOS), Mike Einziger of Incubus (acoustic guitar on Wake Me Up). No artist names in Suno style prompts — use genre/era descriptors.", "songs": [{"title": "Levels", "album": "Levels (Single)", "year": 2011, "bpm": 126, "vibe": "Generation-defining EDM anthem · Etta James gospel sample · Grammy nominated", "dna": "Progressive house track built around a synth lead motif. The vocal sample was lifted from Etta James's 'Something's Got a Hold on Me' (1962) — Avicii discovered it via Pretty Lights and was drawn to its timeless and raw quality. Premiered on Pete Tong's BBC Radio 1 Essential Mix December 2010. Reached top 10 in 13+ countries. Grammy nominated Best Dance Recording 2013. Featured in the Arrow TV pilot. Billboard called it 'the dance anthem of the summer festival season 2011.' Flo Rida sampled it for his hit 'Good Feeling' — bringing it to pop radio a second time.", "style_prompt": "Euphoric progressive house EDM, 126 BPM, ascending melodic synth lead hook, four-on-the-floor kick drum, gospel-soul female vocal sample chopped into breakdown, sweeping synth build to euphoric drop, no vocals in verses — purely instrumental drive, uplifting C major, festival anthem energy, wide stadium production, warm analog synth tone, tension-build-release structure, 2011 progressive house sound", "lyric_prompt": "Write a lyric generation prompt for a euphoric EDM anthem built on the feeling of pure elevation — a moment where everything in life clicks and you feel an overwhelming rush of joy you have never felt before. The lyric should be minimal and anthemic: short, chantable phrases that work over a pulsing four-on-the-floor beat. The emotional core is the feeling described in classic gospel and soul — being seized by an inexplicable good feeling that lifts you above everything. Structure: brief verse setting the scene → chorus built on the central feeling phrase → second verse → final drop with hook returning. Under 3:30. The hook must be singable by 50,000 people simultaneously."}, {"title": "Fade Into Darkness", "album": "Fade Into Darkness (Single)", "year": 2011, "bpm": 128, "vibe": "Samples Penguin Cafe Orchestra · emotional progressive house · Leona Lewis controversy", "dna": "Samples 'Perpetuum Mobile' by Penguin Cafe Orchestra (1987) — an unusual classical source for EDM. This sample was at the center of the 'Collide' controversy when Leona Lewis used it without crediting Avicii; the dispute was settled out of court and Collide became a joint release. Features vocals from Andreas Moe. Demonstrates Avicii's early ability to blend classical and orchestral sources into house music. Premiered at Ultra Music Festival 2011.", "style_prompt": "Early progressive house, 128 BPM, orchestral classical string motif sampled and woven into house production, four-on-the-floor kick, male emotional tenor vocal, ascending melodic line building to euphoric drop, tension between classical restraint and EDM energy, warm nostalgic production, major key uplift, 2011 pre-True Avicii sound, emotional and cinematic", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the fear of losing yourself — of slowly fading away from who you are because of circumstances, relationships, or the relentless pace of life. The narrator stands at the edge of that disappearance and is fighting against it. The verses describe the feeling of fading: things that once mattered becoming distant, the self becoming harder to find. The chorus is the defiant refusal to disappear — or the poignant acknowledgment that it's happening anyway. Include a bridge where a moment of clarity cuts through the fog. The language should feel cinematic and slightly orchestral in its imagery. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "Wake Me Up", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 124, "vibe": "Folk-EDM crossover · Aloe Blacc vocal · topped charts in 20+ countries", "dna": "Avicii's boldest genre experiment: a country/folk-acoustic song transformed into an EDM crossover hit. Features vocals by Aloe Blacc and acoustic guitar performed by Mike Einziger of Incubus. Initially divided critics but topped charts in over 20 countries, became one of the most-streamed songs of the decade, and opened the door for all genre-bending EDM. D major, 124 BPM. Debuted number 1 in the UK. Over 2.5 billion Spotify streams.", "style_prompt": "Folk-EDM crossover, 124 BPM, acoustic guitar-forward intro transforming into massive four-on-the-floor drop, warm soul-gospel male tenor vocal, acoustic guitar by rock guitarist, organic folk texture in verses contrasting with electronic euphoria in chorus, major key, warm and emotional, strummed acoustic guitar over house beat, anthemic singalong chorus, 2013 genre-defying True-era sound", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about feeling lost and searching for direction in life — not knowing where you belong, feeling like you're sleepwalking through the wrong existence, and the desperate wish to be woken up to your real purpose and real feelings. The verses feel folk and intimate, the chorus erupts with EDM intensity. The emotional core is yearning for self-discovery. The chorus hook should be a chantable call about waking up and feeling something real. Include a bridge about the journey not yet complete but the direction finally clear. Under 4:15."}, {"title": "You Make Me", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 123, "vibe": "Pure house energy · Salvatore Ganacci collaboration · electro-house euphoria", "dna": "The most purely electronic track on True — a departure from the album's folk-crossover experiments. Co-written with Salvatore Ganacci. Released as the second single from True. Electro-house energy more aligned with his pre-True DJ set sound. Features a heavy filtered lead synth build typical of peak-era Avicii festival productions. Reached number 2 in the UK Singles Chart.", "style_prompt": "Euphoric electro-house, 123 BPM, heavy filtered lead synth build, four-on-the-floor kick, female vocal lead, major key festival energy, most purely electronic True album track, 2013 peak-era festival EDM, wide synth bass, driving sidechained groove, hands-in-the-air uplift", "lyric_prompt": "Write a euphoric house anthem about the transformative effect someone has on you — how their presence makes you feel things you didn't know you could feel, makes you more alive, more free, more yourself. The lyric should be joyful and slightly breathless. The verses describe specific moments of feeling transformed. The chorus is the declaration of what they do to you — pure euphoric feeling expressed simply and anthemically. Under 3:55. Pure festival energy."}, {"title": "Hey Brother", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 128, "vibe": "Country-folk EDM hybrid · Dan Tyminski vocal · banjo and fiddle over house beat", "dna": "Features vocals from Dan Tyminski — the voice of George Clooney's character in O Brother, Where Art Thou? Incorporates banjo, fiddle, and acoustic guitar into a progressive house framework. The lyric addresses sibling devotion and unconditional loyalty. One of Avicii's most emotionally direct True songs. Reached number 6 on UK Singles Chart.", "style_prompt": "Country-folk progressive house hybrid, 128 BPM, banjo and fiddle over four-on-the-floor kick drum, acoustic guitar strumming, powerful male country-soul tenor vocal, sibling devotion lyric, organic folk instrumentation in verses transforming into EDM drop, warm major key, anthemic chorus with gospel energy, bluegrass meets festival EDM", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about unconditional loyalty and devotion between two people — framed as sibling love but applicable to any profound bond. Earnest and direct: no irony, pure feeling. The verses describe the depth of the bond: growing up together, being there through hard times, protecting each other. The chorus is a declaration — no matter what, I will always be there. The production fuses country-folk acoustic warmth with EDM energy. Include one verse about distance and still being present emotionally. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "Addicted To You", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 126, "vibe": "80s-influenced pop-house · Audra Mae vocal · chart hit in Germany and Belgium", "dna": "Features Audra Mae on vocals — a country-influenced singer whose voice gives the track unusual warmth for EDM. 80s new wave and classic pop influences more apparent here than on any other True track. The production has a retro shimmer under the house kick. Reached number 3 in Germany and Belgium. One of the True album's most pop-forward tracks.", "style_prompt": "80s-influenced pop-house, 126 BPM, retro shimmer synth pads, four-on-the-floor kick, warm female country-pop vocal lead, classic pop melodic structure inside EDM framework, major key euphoria, nostalgic production, less aggressive than festival EDM — more radio-pop warmth, layered harmonies on chorus, 2013 progressive house with 80s gloss", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about being completely addicted to someone — not in a toxic way, but in the way where you simply cannot imagine life without them and don't want to. The tone is warm and slightly breathless — overwhelmed by the feeling rather than analyzing it. The verses describe specific moments of that addiction: thinking about them constantly, everything reminding you of them. The chorus is a declaration of helpless devotion — and the narrator doesn't want to be cured. Include 80s pop influences: a big anthemic hook with backing harmonies. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "Dear Boy", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 125, "vibe": "Deeper melodic house · extended 7:59 runtime · fan favourite · patient progressive structure", "dna": "One of Avicii's most musically sophisticated True tracks and a consistent fan favourite despite not being a major single. A slower-burn progressive house track with extended instrumental sections and a delayed vocal payoff. Demonstrates his mastery of tension and release over longer structures. At 7:59 it is the longest track on True. The patient build — nearly five minutes before the drop — was unusually restrained for commercial EDM.", "style_prompt": "Melodic progressive house, 125 BPM, extended atmospheric build — most of the track is instrumental, delayed vocal entry, lush synth pads, four-on-the-floor drive, warm house bassline, ethereal male vocal when it arrives, major key emotional uplift, deep progressive structure, patient 7-minute tension build to euphoric release", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song addressed to someone going through a hard time who needs to be reminded of their worth — tender and encouraging, not patronizing. The narrator sees this person's potential more clearly than they see it themselves. The verses describe what the narrator observes: the person's resilience, their kindness, the way they underestimate themselves. The chorus is an uplift — a declaration of belief in them. The lyric should be sparse and land with weight — every word earns its place. Include one bridge where the narrator shares their own vulnerability. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Liar Liar", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 124, "vibe": "Mac Davis vocal · classic country storytelling in EDM framework", "dna": "Features legendary country songwriter Mac Davis on vocals. Mac Davis wrote 'A Little Less Conversation' and 'In the Ghetto' for Elvis Presley, making this one of the more surprising True collaborations. His authentic country rasp gives the track a genuinely weathered feel unusual for EDM. The lyric is a classic cheating/lying narrative delivered in the old-school country tradition.", "style_prompt": "Country-EDM hybrid, 124 BPM, classic country rasp vocal lead — authentically weathered not polished pop, four-on-the-floor building under acoustic country texture, True-era Avicii folk-EDM approach, major key, cheating/lying narrative in old-school country tradition, organic country warmth building to electronic chorus drop", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song in the classic country storytelling tradition about catching someone in a lie — the slow accumulation of evidence, the confrontation, the moment of admission. The narrator is not angry — they are tired and a little heartbroken, telling the story plainly. The vocal should feel authentic and weathered, not polished pop. The chorus is the simple declaration: liar, liar. Include specific details that make the lie feel real. The production sits between country acoustic and EDM drop. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Shame On Me", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 125, "vibe": "Agnes vocal · self-recrimination and regret · mid-album emotional dip", "dna": "Features Agnes — a Swedish pop singer. One of the True album's more introspective tracks, sitting at the emotional midpoint of the album where the tone shifts from euphoric to more reflective. The lyric is about self-recrimination — the narrator blaming themselves for the failure of a relationship. Agnes's voice has an unusual plaintive quality that suits the subject matter.", "style_prompt": "Introspective pop-house, 125 BPM, Swedish female pop vocal lead with plaintive quality, True-era Avicii production — warmer and less aggressive than festival tracks, mid-tempo with emotional weight, minor emotional undertone, self-recrimination lyric, house groove with organic warmth", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about self-recrimination — the narrator fully owning their role in the failure of a relationship, refusing to blame the other person. The tone is honest and tired, not dramatic. The verses catalogue the specific things the narrator did wrong: the moments of selfishness, the times they didn't show up, the small betrayals that accumulated. The chorus is the admission of responsibility. Under 4:15."}, {"title": "Lay Me Down", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 127, "vibe": "Adam Lambert vocal · epic progressive house · swelling theatrical EDM", "dna": "Features Adam Lambert — his theatrical vocal range gives the track a distinctly operatic quality unusual for EDM. One of the True album's most sonically ambitious tracks with a sweeping progressive house production. Lambert's vocal performance is the most theatrically dramatic on the album. The track builds to one of Avicii's most epic drops.", "style_prompt": "Epic progressive house with theatrical vocal, 127 BPM, Adam Lambert-style operatic male tenor range, sweeping building production, four-on-the-floor escalating to massive theatrical drop, major key grandeur, True-era Avicii ambition, orchestral-feeling synth swells, most dramatically scored True track", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the complete surrender to love — laying down every wall, every defense, every pretense, because this person has made all of it unnecessary. The tone is theatrical and emotionally enormous — this is not a quiet love song, it's an aria. The verses build toward the moment of surrender. The chorus is the act itself — laying down, fully open, fully trusting. Adam Lambert-style: big emotions delivered with full theatrical commitment. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Hope There's Someone", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 126, "vibe": "Antony and the Johnsons cover · Linnea Henriksson vocal · most haunting True moment", "dna": "A cover of Antony and the Johnsons' 2005 Mercury Prize-winning song 'Hope There's Someone.' Features Swedish singer Linnea Henriksson on vocals. The original is one of the most haunting songs of the 2000s — about the fear of dying alone. Avicii transforms it into a progressive house production while preserving the lyric's existential weight. One of the most sonically ambitious and emotionally serious moments on True.", "style_prompt": "Haunting progressive house cover, 126 BPM, delicate ethereal Swedish female vocal, four-on-the-floor underlying a fragile melody, True-era Avicii production serving rather than overwhelming the emotional weight, major key but existentially serious lyric about fear of dying alone, slowly building drop that feels almost reverent, extended 6-minute runtime", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the most fundamental human fear — the fear of dying alone, without someone to witness your life and hold your hand at the end. The tone is not morbid but nakedly honest and searingly tender. The verses describe the specific loneliness of that fear: waking up at 3am and reaching for someone who isn't there. The chorus is the hope itself — the prayer that there will be someone. The most emotionally serious and haunting song in the set. Under 6:30."}, {"title": "Heart Upon My Sleeve", "album": "True", "year": 2013, "bpm": 126, "vibe": "MØ and Dan Reynolds vocal · True album closer · vulnerability anthem", "dna": "Features MØ and Dan Reynolds of Imagine Dragons (a different version appears on TIM featuring only Imagine Dragons). The True version features both artists. The True album closer — a vulnerability anthem about being completely open with someone. At 126 BPM it sits firmly in the sweet spot of Avicii's melodic house range. One of the more pop-forward True tracks with a strong hook.", "style_prompt": "Pop-house vulnerability anthem, 126 BPM, female and male vocal alternating, emotional openness as lyric theme, True-era Avicii warm production, major key, four-on-the-floor, catchy hook-forward structure, melodic lead synth, True album closer energy — summary of the album's emotional journey", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about complete emotional vulnerability — wearing your heart on your sleeve, showing someone exactly who you are without hiding anything. The narrator has decided to stop protecting themselves and just be completely open. The verses describe what that openness feels like: terrifying and liberating simultaneously. The chorus is the declaration of openness. Include a moment where the vulnerability is met with warmth rather than rejection. Under 4:45."}, {"title": "Waiting For Love", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 129, "vibe": "Stories lead single · Simon Aldred vocal · Sunday morning warmth to festival drop", "dna": "One of the defining songs of the Stories era. Features vocals from Simon Aldred of Cherry Ghost. 129 BPM. Built around the contrast between quiet Sunday morning domesticity in the verses and the euphoric festival drop in the chorus. Avicii described the Stories album as being about the journey of life through its stories. Reached number 4 in the UK.", "style_prompt": "Warm melodic house, 129 BPM, intimate acoustic-feeling verse with warm male indie-folk vocal, contrasting with euphoric festival drop on chorus, four-on-the-floor kick, ascending synth lead on drop, major key emotional warmth, soft Sunday morning atmosphere in verses building to festival energy, Stories-era warmer more melodic Avicii production", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the beautiful in-between state of waiting — the uncertainty before something transformative arrives: love, purpose, a moment that changes everything. The narrator is in the quiet period before the breakthrough, and there is a warm acceptance in the waiting. The verses describe the quiet ordinary days of that waiting period. The chorus erupts into the certainty that it is coming — the faith that the waiting will be worth it. Include imagery of Sunday morning quiet contrasted with the enormity of what is approaching. Under 3:45."}, {"title": "Talk to Myself", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 108, "vibe": "Gavin DeGraw vocal · talking through absence · slower introspective Stories track", "dna": "Features Gavin DeGraw. One of the slower, more introspective Stories tracks at 108 BPM. About the experience of missing someone so profoundly that you find yourself talking to them as if they were still present. Gavin DeGraw's soulful voice gives it a blues-adjacent warmth unusual for the album. One of Stories' more emotionally direct tracks.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo soulful pop-house, 108 BPM, Gavin DeGraw-style soulful male vocal, blues-adjacent warmth in EDM framework, Stories-era Avicii slower introspective production, absence and longing as lyric theme, warm groove with emotional weight, major key but melancholic feeling", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about missing someone so profoundly that you talk to them even when they're not there — filling the silence with one-sided conversations, imagining their responses. The narrator is not delusional — they know the person isn't there — but the habit of speaking to them is the last remnant of the relationship. The verses catalogue specific moments of these conversations: in the car, late at night, looking at something that would have made them laugh. The chorus is the admission of what's happening. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Touch Me", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 116, "vibe": "Vargas & Lagola vocal · longing for physical connection · warm production", "dna": "Features Vargas & Lagola (Vincent Pontare and Salem Al Fakir) — Swedish songwriting duo who would become key TIM collaborators. One of the more mid-tempo Stories tracks. About the longing for physical connection — the specific ache of wanting to be touched by someone. Warm, sensual production that sits somewhere between pop-house and tropical house.", "style_prompt": "Warm mid-tempo pop-house, 116 BPM, Vargas and Lagola-style Swedish pop male vocal, warm sensual production, longing for physical connection lyric, Stories-era Avicii warm palette, four-on-the-floor with tropical warmth, melodic lead synth, major key warmth", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the specific ache of wanting to be physically close to someone — not just emotional connection but the hunger for their physical presence, their touch. The tone is warm and honest rather than overtly sexual. The verses describe the distance and what makes it hard: the remembered feeling of closeness, the everyday moments that trigger the longing. The chorus is the simple direct statement of desire. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Ten More Days", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 138, "vibe": "Zac Brown vocal · country gospel EDM · counting down to reunion", "dna": "Features Zac Brown of the Zac Brown Band — bringing authentic country star power to the Stories album. The most overtly country-inflected Stories track, continuing the True-era folk-EDM experiment with a different angle. 138 BPM — one of the faster Stories tracks. The lyric is about counting down the days until you can be with someone again.", "style_prompt": "Country-EDM hybrid, 138 BPM, Zac Brown-style authentic country male vocal, faster Stories track, country guitar texture over four-on-the-floor kick, warm major key, countdown-to-reunion lyric, gospel-inflected chorus, Stories-era Avicii country experiment continuing the True tradition", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about counting down the days until you can be with someone again — the specific anticipation of reunion, the way every day feels simultaneously too slow and somehow precious because it brings you closer. The verses describe the current situation of separation: what you're doing, how you're managing, what reminds you of them. The chorus is the countdown itself — specific, hopeful, urgent. Include a bridge where the day finally arrives. Under 4:05."}, {"title": "For a Better Day", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 135, "vibe": "Alex Ebert vocal · child abuse and healing · most emotionally serious Stories track", "dna": "Written by Avicii and Alex Ebert of Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros. The most emotionally serious Stories track — about child abuse, survival, and the hope for healing. Alex Ebert's ethereal vocal quality gives it a tender, aching feel. The lyric tells a specific story of a survivor finding a way forward. Avicii said this was one of his most personally meaningful tracks. Official video depicted child trafficking and abuse awareness.", "style_prompt": "Emotionally serious melodic house, 135 BPM, Alex Ebert-style ethereal indie-folk male vocal, tender and aching production, child-abuse-survival-and-healing lyric, Stories-era Avicii warm production serving difficult content, four-on-the-floor but gentle, major key hope through pain, most emotionally serious Stories track", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about surviving childhood trauma and finding a way toward healing — about a child or young person who endured something terrible but who holds onto the promise of a better day ahead. The tone is tender and hopeful rather than dark — this is the survivor's perspective, not the wound's perspective. The verses describe the experience in delicate but honest terms. The chorus is the promise: there will be a better day. Include an adult perspective looking back on the child they were. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "Broken Arrows", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 116, "vibe": "Zac Brown vocal · darkness and light duality · deep cut fan favourite", "dna": "Features Zac Brown again in his second Stories appearance. One of the most beloved deep cuts on Stories. The broken arrows metaphor — things aimed at a target that didn't reach it, paths not taken — is used to address the duality of darkness and light, of loss and resilience. The lyric 'I've seen the darkness in the light' is one of the most quoted lines from the album. Reached number 14 in the US on the Dance chart.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo emotional melodic house, 116 BPM, Zac Brown authentic country vocal, darkness-and-light duality lyric, G major key, Stories-era warm production, broken arrows as resilience metaphor, four-on-the-floor with emotional weight, ascending hook on chorus", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song using broken arrows as a central metaphor — things that were aimed true but didn't reach their target: missed opportunities, failed relationships, paths not taken. The narrator has been one of those broken arrows and is finding a way to be whole again. The lyric should explore the duality of darkness and light — that you can see the darkness even inside the light, but also find light inside the darkness. The chorus is the declaration of not walking alone through this. Under 3:52."}, {"title": "True Believer", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 123, "vibe": "Matisyahu vocal · faith and conviction · most genre-diverse Stories track", "dna": "Features Matisyahu — the Hasidic Jewish reggae-rap artist. The most genre-diverse Stories track: reggae, rap, and EDM in one production. Matisyahu's vocal style — a blend of beatboxing, rap, and singing — gives the track a unique texture. About the conviction of belief and the strength that comes from it. One of the more unusual collaborations in the Avicii catalog.", "style_prompt": "Reggae-rap EDM hybrid, 123 BPM, Matisyahu-style Hasidic reggae-rap-singing vocal blend, most genre-diverse Stories track, four-on-the-floor under reggae influence, faith and conviction lyric, Stories-era warm production, major key uplift, unusual vocal beatbox-sing texture", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the strength that comes from deep conviction — being a true believer in something larger than yourself, whether that's a spiritual faith, a love, a cause, or a vision for the world. The tone is uplifting and certain, not preachy. The verses describe what it feels like to hold that belief even when the world pushes back. The chorus is the declaration of belief. Include a reggae-influenced lyric rhythm. Under 4:48."}, {"title": "City Lights", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 128, "vibe": "Wyclef Jean vocal · city as dreamscape · longest Stories track at 6:28", "dna": "Features Wyclef Jean. Longest Stories track at 6:28. G minor key — one of the few minor-key tracks on an album otherwise dominated by major keys. About the city as a dreamscape of possibility and lost souls. Wyclef's Caribbean-inflected delivery gives it a warm global feel. The extended length allows for a longer build and more atmospheric development than typical Avicii tracks.", "style_prompt": "Extended atmospheric melodic house, 128 BPM, Wyclef Jean-style Caribbean-inflected male vocal, G minor key — rare minor key for Avicii, city-as-dreamscape lyric, Stories-era production with extended 6-minute development, warm global production, atmospheric build before euphoric drop, lost-souls-in-the-city theme", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about a city at night as a dreamscape — a place where every light in every window represents a story, a longing, a life. The narrator moves through this city feeling both part of something enormous and utterly alone. The verses describe specific images: the neon reflections, the strangers who brush past, the sense of infinite possibility and infinite loneliness coexisting. The chorus is the paradox of the city: everything and nothing, together and alone. Under 6:30."}, {"title": "Pure Grinding", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 104, "vibe": "Hip-hop-soul-EDM collision · Earl St. Clair vocal · most urban Stories track", "dna": "Features Kristoffer Fogelmark and Earl St. Clair — the most hip-hop-influenced track in Avicii's studio album catalog. Described as a collision of hip-hop, soul and electronic sounds. More urban and groove-oriented than typical Avicii. D major, 104 BPM — the slower tempo gives it a more menacing, grinding groove. One of the more experimental Stories tracks.", "style_prompt": "Hip-hop soul EDM collision, 104 BPM, grinding groove, D major, male hip-hop-soul vocal, most urban Avicii production, four-on-the-floor with hip-hop swagger, bass-heavy menacing groove, Stories-era production pushed toward urban territory, soul-inflected hook", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the relentless daily grind — the hard work, the hustle, the pure grinding effort of building something when everything is against you. The tone has hip-hop swagger: confident, uncompromising, proud of the struggle. The verses describe the specific effort and sacrifice. The chorus is the declaration of what you're grinding toward and why it's worth it. More urban and groove-oriented than typical EDM. Under 2:55."}, {"title": "Sunset Jesus", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 105, "vibe": "Alex Ebert vocal · aspiration and upward mobility · billboard as symbol", "dna": "Features Alex Ebert again in his second Stories appearance. The lyric's central image is of someone on a bus looking up at a billboard and seeing a face that could be theirs — the longing for upward mobility and recognition. 'Staring at the billboard from the bus / Looking at the faces, thinking that could be any one of us.' One of the more aspirational Stories tracks.", "style_prompt": "Warm aspirational melodic house, 105 BPM, Alex Ebert ethereal indie-folk vocal, upward-mobility and aspiration lyric, Stories-era Avicii warm production, G major, four-on-the-floor with organic warmth, billboard-as-aspiration imagery, gentle euphoric drop", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about aspiration and the longing to become more than your current circumstances allow — looking up at those who have made it and believing that could be you. The central image is a bus, a billboard, faces of people who seem to have everything, and the honest ambition to reach that place. The tone is hopeful and unashamed of wanting more. The chorus is the prayer for hope on the journey. Include a verse about giving back when you get there. Under 4:24."}, {"title": "Can't Catch Me", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 80, "vibe": "Slowest Stories track · Shadow Child vocal · running from the past", "dna": "Slowest track on Stories at 80 BPM. Features Shadow Child on vocals. About running from the past — the feeling of finally outrunning the things that have been chasing you. The slower tempo gives it a more brooding, introspective quality compared to the rest of the album.", "style_prompt": "Slow brooding pop-house, 80 BPM, G# major, slowest Stories track, male vocal with brooding introspective quality, running-from-the-past lyric, Stories-era Avicii slower atmospheric production, minimal four-on-the-floor, emotionally heavy despite major key", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about finally outrunning the things that have been chasing you — old mistakes, old pain, old versions of yourself. The narrator has been running for a long time and has finally reached a point where the past can't catch them anymore. The verses describe what was chasing them: specific regrets, specific failures, specific losses. The chorus is the declaration of freedom — you can't catch me anymore. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Somewhere in Stockholm", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 128, "vibe": "Axwell vocal · Swedish homeland tribute · emotional numbness and alcohol", "dna": "Features Axwell of Swedish House Mafia — a rare collaboration between two of Sweden's biggest EDM exports. The lyric contains one of the most quoted Avicii lines: 'I'm from a place where we never openly show our emotions / We drown our sorrows in bottomless bottles and leave them to float in the ocean.' A rare moment of cultural self-examination — the Swedish emotional reserve and relationship with alcohol — delivered with raw honesty.", "style_prompt": "Anthemic melodic house, 128 BPM, G major, Axwell-style Swedish EDM vocal energy, Swedish cultural emotional-reserve lyric — rare cultural self-examination, Stories-era warm production, four-on-the-floor, bottles-and-oceans imagery, emotional numbness as subject matter, festival-scale anthem", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about a cultural or personal tendency to suppress emotions and drown sorrows rather than face them — specifically the Nordic/Scandinavian relationship with emotional reserve and alcohol as a coping mechanism. The narrator recognizes this pattern in themselves and their people, delivering it with honest self-awareness rather than shame. The central image is of sorrows drowned in bottles, left to float in the ocean. The chorus is the acknowledgment of this pattern — and perhaps the beginning of changing it. Under 3:22."}, {"title": "Trouble", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 116, "vibe": "Wayne Hector vocal · drawn to dangerous love · shortest Stories track", "dna": "Features Wayne Hector — Irish songwriter and vocalist. Shortest Stories track at 2:51. A minor key emotional track — about knowing someone is trouble but being unable to stay away. A major key but with a darker emotional undercurrent. One of the Stories album's more vulnerable tracks about being drawn to someone who isn't good for you.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo vulnerable pop-house, 116 BPM, A major, warm male pop vocal, knowing-they're-trouble-but-can't-stay-away lyric, Stories-era production, short under 3 minutes, four-on-the-floor with emotional weight, major key with darker emotional undercurrent", "lyric_prompt": "Write a short song about being drawn irresistibly to someone you know is trouble — knowing it will end badly, knowing you should stay away, and choosing to go anyway. The tone is honest and a little helpless: not celebrating self-destruction, just acknowledging it. The verses describe the specific qualities that make them irresistible despite being dangerous. The chorus is the admission. Under 2:55."}, {"title": "Gonna Love Ya", "album": "Stories", "year": 2015, "bpm": 100, "vibe": "Vargas & Lagola vocal · album closer · quiet devotion promise", "dna": "Features Vargas & Lagola. Stories album closer. A quieter, more restrained closing track than most Avicii productions. The lyric is a simple, direct promise of love. D# minor key gives it a more melancholic quality than typical Avicii closers. Works as a tonal resolution to the album's journey — after all the stories told, the closing promise.", "style_prompt": "Quiet restrained pop-house album closer, 100 BPM, D# minor, Vargas and Lagola warm Swedish vocal, simple direct devotion promise lyric, Stories-era production at its most restrained, four-on-the-floor but quiet, minor key melancholy under simple love declaration, closing-statement feel", "lyric_prompt": "Write a quiet, restrained song that functions as an album-closing promise — a simple declaration that after everything, the narrator is going to love someone fully and completely. The tone is gentle and certain rather than dramatic. The verses acknowledge the journey that has brought them here. The chorus is the promise itself — 'gonna love ya' — simple, direct, completely meant. Under 4 minutes. The quiet resolution after a long journey."}, {"title": "Friend of Mine", "album": "AVĪCI (01) EP", "year": 2017, "bpm": 120, "vibe": "AVICI EP opener · Vargas & Lagola · guitar-driven live-band aesthetic", "dna": "Opens the AVĪCI (01) EP — Avicii's final studio release before his death. The EP marked a stylistic shift toward organic, guitar-driven productions with live instrumentation. Features Vargas & Lagola who co-wrote most of the EP. The 'friend of mine' lyric explores how relationships evolve over time — specifically the transformative nature of close friendship.", "style_prompt": "Guitar-driven organic pop-house, 120 BPM, live-band aesthetic — real guitar prominent, Vargas and Lagola warm Swedish vocal, AVICI EP final-era Avicii sound, organic rather than purely electronic, warm four-on-the-floor, friendship-and-transformation lyric, warm major key, intimate production scale", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about a deep friendship that has changed you — the specific way one person's presence in your life has made you better, different, more fully yourself. The narrator is addressing this friend directly: listing the specific ways they have transformed each other over time. The chorus is the declaration of what this friendship means. Include a verse about a specific moment when the friendship proved itself. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Lonely Together", "album": "AVĪCI (01) EP", "year": 2017, "bpm": 120, "vibe": "Rita Ora feature · melancholic club anthem · shared loneliness", "dna": "Features Rita Ora. One of Avicii's most commercially successful late-period tracks. 120 BPM — slightly slower, giving it a more melancholic, late-night feel. The theme explores two lonely people choosing to be lonely together rather than apart — finding comfort in shared emptiness. The production has a darker, more nocturnal quality than earlier work. Debuted at number 1 in Sweden.", "style_prompt": "Melancholic melodic house, 120 BPM, darker late-night production, female pop vocal lead with emotional edge, four-on-the-floor but slower and more introspective, minor key undertones under pop-EDM structure, two-people-in-shared-loneliness lyric, 2017 AVICI era more emotionally complex, nocturnal club atmosphere, bittersweet rather than euphoric", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about two people who are both deeply lonely finding each other and choosing to be lonely together — sharing their solitude rather than suffering it alone. This is not a happy love story; it's a realistic one: two people who don't have what they truly need but have found something real in each other's company. The verses establish both perspectives: their individual loneliness, the moment they recognize it in each other. The chorus is the decision — let's not fix this, let's just be in it together. Include a bridge where the nature of this connection is questioned and then accepted. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "You Be Love", "album": "AVĪCI (01) EP", "year": 2017, "bpm": 114, "vibe": "Billy Raffoul vocal · role division in relationship · organic guitar-house", "dna": "Features Billy Raffoul — a Canadian rock-influenced singer-songwriter. The guitar-forward AVICI EP aesthetic at its most rock-adjacent. The lyric is about the division of roles in a relationship — you be love, I'll be the strength; a negotiation of what each person brings. Billy Raffoul's rawer rock vocal distinguishes it from the polished pop of earlier Avicii collaborations.", "style_prompt": "Organic rock-adjacent pop-house, 114 BPM, Billy Raffoul raw rock-influenced male vocal, guitar-forward AVICI EP aesthetic, role-division-in-relationship lyric, warmer and rawer than peak Avicii EDM, four-on-the-floor with live rock energy, major key emotional directness", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the negotiation of roles in a relationship — the conscious decision about what each person will be for the other. You be the love, I'll be the strength; you be the warmth, I'll be the foundation. The lyric is a tender negotiation of interdependence. The verses describe what each person needs and what they can give. The chorus is the agreement — a contract of mutual support. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Without You", "album": "AVĪCI (01) EP", "year": 2017, "bpm": 126, "vibe": "Sandro Cavazza · late-era introspection · number 1 in Sweden", "dna": "Features Sandro Cavazza — a frequent final-years collaborator. The AVĪCI era represented a move toward more introspective, emotionally vulnerable production. Less festival-focused, more quietly devastating. About being unable to function without a specific person and the specific emptiness of that absence. Debuted at number 1 in Sweden.", "style_prompt": "Late-era melodic house, 126 BPM, warm intimate production less festival-focused than True era, Sandro Cavazza warm male vocal, four-on-the-floor but softer, introspective personal rather than anthemic, 2017 AVICI EP sound — mature emotionally sophisticated, quiet devastating EDM", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the specific emptiness of life without one particular person — not dramatic heartbreak but the quiet pervasive way their absence changes everything. Every ordinary thing reminds you of them. The world still functions but feels fundamentally wrong. The verses catalogue specific moments of daily life hollowed out by their absence. The chorus is the central admission: without this person, the narrator is diminished — not destroyed, just incomplete. The tone is mature and honest, not teenage. Include a bridge where the narrator considers whether this dependency is healthy and decides it doesn't matter. Under 3:45."}, {"title": "What Would I Change It To", "album": "AVĪCI (01) EP", "year": 2017, "bpm": 117, "vibe": "AlunaGeorge vocal · questioning identity and change · introspective EP closer", "dna": "Features AlunaGeorge (Aluna Francis). The most introspective AVICI EP track — asking what you would change about yourself if you could. The question turns out to have a complicated answer: maybe nothing, or maybe everything. AlunaGeorge's distinctive electronic-soul vocal style gives it a unique texture in the Avicii catalog.", "style_prompt": "Introspective electronic-soul house, 117 BPM, AlunaGeorge-style electronic-soul female vocal, AVICI EP organic production, identity and self-questioning lyric, major key but contemplative feeling, four-on-the-floor with soul texture, what-would-I-change existential question", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song built on the question 'what would I change it to?' — if you could change who you are, what would you actually change? The narrator explores this question honestly: the things they would change (the fears, the flaws, the damage), and then discovers that the answer is more complicated than expected. Maybe the things you'd change are also the things that made you who you are. The chorus is the question itself, held open. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Peace of Mind", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 126, "vibe": "TIM opener · Vargas & Lagola · best TIM production per critics", "dna": "Opens TIM. Features Vargas & Lagola who are credited by critics as delivering the best production on the posthumous album. Critics noted it as 'one of the few TIM songs that feels most like a classic Avicii track.' The lyric is about finding peace of mind — calming the internal noise and finding stillness. The opening track sets an aspirational tone for the posthumous album.", "style_prompt": "Classic Avicii-feeling posthumous melodic house, 126 BPM, Vargas and Lagola warm Swedish male vocal, TIM opening statement energy, four-on-the-floor, ascending melodic synth, peace-of-mind and internal stillness lyric, warm major key, best TIM production — feels most like peak Avicii", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about finding peace of mind — the specific experience of quieting the internal noise, the worries, the racing thoughts, and finding stillness. The narrator has been searching for this peace and describes what the search has looked like: the attempts that didn't work, the unexpected moment when stillness finally arrived. The chorus is the arrival at peace. Include the idea that peace isn't the absence of problems but the ability to hold them without being destroyed by them. Under 3:01."}, {"title": "Heaven", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 124, "vibe": "Posthumous · Simon Aldred vocal · searching for belonging and peace", "dna": "From TIM. Features Simon Aldred of Cherry Ghost — the vocalist from Waiting For Love. Released posthumously. Written about searching for a place that feels like home — a state of peace and belonging. Given the context of Avicii's death, the song carries additional weight. Warm and emotionally generous production typical of his later Aldred collaborations.", "style_prompt": "Warm melodic house, 124 BPM, Simon Aldred English indie-folk male vocal warm and searching, four-on-the-floor with emotional gentleness, ascending melodic synth hook, major key warmth, TIM-era posthumous production, searching-for-peace lyric, festival scale but intimate emotional register", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about searching for a place — physical or emotional — that finally feels like home. The narrator has been moving through the world feeling like a visitor everywhere, belonging nowhere, until they discover what heaven means to them: a specific person, a specific moment, a specific feeling of peace. The verses catalogue the search and the longing. The chorus is the moment of arrival — the declaration that this, finally, is heaven. Include a bridge where the narrator reflects on how long the search took. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "SOS", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 126, "vibe": "Aloe Blacc reunion · posthumous · cry for help as euphoric anthem · mental health anthem", "dna": "From TIM. Features Aloe Blacc — the vocalist from Wake Me Up — making it a poignant reunion. Written about needing help and being unable to ask for it — widely interpreted as autobiographical given Avicii's documented struggles with anxiety and the pressures of fame. Reached number 1 on US Hot Dance/Electronic Songs. All album profits go to the Tim Bergling Foundation for mental health awareness.", "style_prompt": "Emotional melodic house, 126 BPM, soul-gospel male tenor vocal, four-on-the-floor kick, ascending melodic synth hook, major key but emotionally complex, posthumous TIM production — polished and emotionally raw simultaneously, cry-for-help lyric inside euphoric EDM framework, festival energy serving a vulnerable message", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about needing help and being unable to ask for it — sending a distress signal that no one around you can read. The narrator is surrounded by people and completely alone in their struggle. The verses describe specific ways this struggle manifests: performing normalcy, the exhaustion of hiding, moments where the mask almost slips. The chorus is the SOS itself — the honest cry for help that the narrator can only express in song, not in person. The production is euphoric EDM, creating powerful tension with the lyric's vulnerability. Include a bridge where the narrator imagines what it would feel like to actually be saved. Under 3:45."}, {"title": "Tough Love", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 126, "vibe": "Agnes and Vargas & Lagola · female vocal TIM lead single · resilience through hardship", "dna": "Features Agnes and Vargas & Lagola. One of TIM's two lead singles alongside SOS. Agnes is a Swedish pop singer best known for the 2008 hit 'Release Me.' The lyric is about resilience — the tough love that life sometimes shows you, making you stronger through difficulty. Reached number 9 on Hot Dance/Electronic Songs.", "style_prompt": "Resilience-themed melodic house TIM lead single, 126 BPM, Agnes-style Swedish pop female vocal bright and clear, four-on-the-floor, ascending melodic hook, major key strength-through-difficulty lyric, TIM-era Vargas and Lagola production, warm but purposeful production", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about resilience — the 'tough love' that difficult experiences show you, making you stronger and more capable than you knew. The tone is grateful for the hardship, not resentful of it. The verses describe specific difficulties that turned out to be teachers. The chorus is the realization: this was tough love, not punishment. Include a bridge where the narrator reflects on who they've become because of what they went through. Under 3:28."}, {"title": "Bad Reputation", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 120, "vibe": "Joe Janiak vocal · owning your story · defiant self-acceptance", "dna": "Features Joe Janiak — an American vocalist. About owning your reputation rather than being defined by it — taking back the narrative that others have created about you. Defiant self-acceptance in the face of judgment. One of TIM's more upbeat, assertive tracks.", "style_prompt": "Upbeat defiant pop-house, 120 BPM, Joe Janiak warm male pop vocal, owning-your-story and self-acceptance lyric, TIM-era warm production, four-on-the-floor, assertive major key energy, defiant rather than defensive", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about taking back your own narrative — owning the 'bad reputation' others have given you rather than being defined by their judgment. The narrator has decided that their reputation, whatever it is, belongs to them and they're not apologizing for it. The verses describe specific judgments and the narrator's response to each. The chorus is the declaration of ownership: this is my reputation, I own it. Under 3:27."}, {"title": "Ain't a Thing", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 122, "vibe": "Bonn vocal · dismissing obstacles · upbeat defiance", "dna": "Features Bonn — a British vocalist who also appears on Freak. About dismissing obstacles and challenges as 'ain't a thing' — the defiant minimization of what stands in the way. More upbeat and assertive than many TIM tracks. One of the more straightforwardly positive productions on the posthumous album.", "style_prompt": "Upbeat defiant pop-house, 122 BPM, Bonn warm British male pop vocal, obstacles-dismissal defiant lyric, TIM-era warm production, four-on-the-floor, major key, positive energy, nothing-can-stop-me attitude", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about dismissing every obstacle that life throws in your path with defiant confidence — nothing is going to stop you, every challenge is 'ain't a thing.' The tone is confident and energetic rather than aggressive. The verses list the specific things that have tried to stop the narrator. The chorus is the dismissal: it ain't a thing. Under 3:03."}, {"title": "Hold the Line", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 120, "vibe": "A R I Z O N A vocal · holding position through difficulty · anthemic perseverance", "dna": "Features indie-pop trio A R I Z O N A. About holding the line — maintaining your position and integrity through difficulty and pressure. One of TIM's more anthemic tracks with an arena-scale feel. A R I Z O N A's melodic indie-pop vocal style gives it a more indie-inflected feel than typical Avicii collaborations.", "style_prompt": "Anthemic perseverance pop-house, 120 BPM, A R I Z O N A indie-pop trio vocal, holding-position-through-difficulty lyric, TIM-era production with indie-pop inflection, four-on-the-floor, major key, arena-scale feel, stand-your-ground theme", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about holding the line — maintaining your integrity, your position, your values, under enormous pressure to abandon them. The narrator is being pushed from every direction and choosing to stay put. The verses describe the specific pressures and temptations to give ground. The chorus is the declaration: I will hold the line. Include a bridge where the cost of holding the line is acknowledged and accepted. Under 2:53."}, {"title": "Freak", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 125, "vibe": "Bonn vocal · embracing difference · the outsider owning their otherness", "dna": "Features Bonn again in his second TIM appearance. About embracing being different — taking the word 'freak' and making it a badge of pride rather than an insult. One of the more playful and upbeat TIM tracks. The self-acceptance theme fits within the broader TIM album narrative about mental health and self-worth.", "style_prompt": "Playful upbeat pop-house, 125 BPM, Bonn warm British male pop vocal, outsider-embracing-difference lyric, TIM-era warm production, four-on-the-floor, major key pride, freak-as-badge-of-honour, self-acceptance and difference celebration", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about embracing being different — taking the things that make you weird, unusual, or a 'freak' and wearing them as a badge of pride. The narrator has been told they're too much, too strange, too different, and has decided to celebrate that rather than hide it. The verses describe specific ways they are 'freakish' with affection and pride. The chorus is the declaration: yes, I'm a freak, and that's exactly right. Under 3:01."}, {"title": "Excuse Me Mr Sir", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 122, "vibe": "Vargas & Lagola · addressing authority and power · second-best TIM production per critics", "dna": "Features Vargas & Lagola. Critics noted this as one of the better TIM productions alongside Peace of Mind. About addressing those in power with a challenge — the 'excuse me' as a deceptively polite confrontation. One of the more subtly political TIM tracks. Vargas & Lagola's production here is warmer and more classic-feeling Avicii.", "style_prompt": "Warm anthemic pop-house, 122 BPM, Vargas and Lagola warm Swedish vocal, deceptively-polite confrontation-of-power lyric, TIM-era production at its most classic-Avicii-feeling, four-on-the-floor, major key, addressing-authority theme with polite defiance", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about addressing power with deceptively polite defiance — the 'excuse me, sir' that is actually a challenge. The narrator is speaking to those in power or authority and, beneath the polite form, delivering a pointed confrontation. The verses describe what the narrator wants to say. The chorus is the polite but unmistakably challenging address. Under 3:09."}, {"title": "Heart Upon My Sleeve", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 126, "vibe": "Imagine Dragons version · TIM version different from True · vulnerability returned", "dna": "The TIM version features Imagine Dragons (Dan Reynolds) — different from the True version which featured MØ and Dan Reynolds together. This version has a more rock-inflected energy reflecting Imagine Dragons' arena-rock style. The lyric remains the same vulnerability anthem but with a more powerful, guitar-driven intensity.", "style_prompt": "Rock-inflected arena pop-house, 126 BPM, Imagine Dragons arena-rock male vocal, vulnerability anthem with more rock power than True version, four-on-the-floor with rock guitar, major key, heart-on-sleeve emotional openness, TIM posthumous version more intense than True original", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about complete emotional vulnerability — wearing your heart on your sleeve, showing someone exactly who you are without any protection. The narrator has decided to stop protecting themselves and just be completely open. The verses build toward the moment of surrender. The chorus is the act itself — fully open, fully trusting. Rock-inflected energy: this is not a quiet confession but a declaration. Under 4:16."}, {"title": "Never Leave Me", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 120, "vibe": "Joe Janiak vocal · fear of abandonment · plea for permanence", "dna": "Features Joe Janiak in his second TIM appearance. About the fear of being left — asking someone to stay, to never leave. The lyric is more vulnerable and pleading than most Avicii productions. One of TIM's more nakedly emotional tracks.", "style_prompt": "Vulnerable emotional pop-house, 120 BPM, Joe Janiak warm male pop vocal, fear-of-abandonment and plea-for-permanence lyric, TIM-era warm production, four-on-the-floor, major key, nakedly emotional rather than anthemic", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song about the fear of being left — asking someone to stay, to never leave, to be a permanent presence. The narrator is not manipulative but genuinely vulnerable: they know how much this person means to them and are honest about their fear of loss. The verses describe what this person brings and what their absence would mean. The chorus is the plea: never leave me. Include a bridge where the narrator acknowledges that this ask may be too much, and makes it anyway. Under 2:53."}, {"title": "Fades Away", "album": "TIM", "year": 2019, "bpm": 120, "vibe": "Noonie Bao vocal · TIM closing track · bittersweet farewell with swelling orchestral production", "dna": "Features Noonie Bao — an Avicii veteran vocalist. The TIM album closer. Described by critics as a 'sad but appropriate way to end Tim.' Noonie Bao bids farewell with swelling orchestral heft. The lyric 'Don't you love it how it all / It all just fades away' serves as a poignant closing statement — both about things fading and about Avicii himself. All profits from TIM go to the Tim Bergling Foundation.", "style_prompt": "Bittersweet orchestral closing melodic house, 120 BPM, Noonie Bao Swedish female vocal — emotional and clear, swelling orchestral production underneath house beat, TIM album closer energy — farewell and acceptance, major key but emotionally bittersweet, fading-away as central metaphor, most orchestrally scored TIM track", "lyric_prompt": "Write a closing song about the bittersweet nature of things fading away — not only the bad things but everything, including the things you love most. The lyric should be the most emotionally generous and accepting song in the set: acknowledging that everything fades, that this is the nature of life, and finding something beautiful in that. The narrator is at peace with impermanence. The chorus is the gentle acknowledgment: don't you love it how it all just fades away. Include a bridge that feels like a final farewell. Under 4 minutes. The last song on the last album."}], "albums": [{"title": "True", "year": 2013, "style_prompt": "Genre-defying folk-EDM crossover debut, four-on-the-floor house kick under acoustic guitar and banjo, gospel-soul vocal or featured singer with emotional warmth, ascending melodic synth lead on drops, major key euphoric uplift, festival anthem scale with folk instrumentation, 123–128 BPM, warm analog production, 2013 True-era sound — the album that took EDM to country radio and pop radio simultaneously", "lyric_prompt": "Write a True-era Avicii song that blends country-folk imagery and emotional directness with EDM energy. The emotional world: searching for identity, longing for belonging, or the euphoric rush of finally feeling free. The verses should feel folk-intimate — acoustic, honest, conversational. The chorus should explode with EDM energy and festival singalong power. The lyric should work equally at a campfire or at a 50,000-person festival. Use imagery from both worlds. Include a bridge that reframes the central emotion. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Stories", "year": 2015, "style_prompt": "Mature melodic house, warmer and more diverse than True, guitar-driven melodic hooks over four-on-the-floor beats, featured vocalists with wide emotional range — country stars, reggae artists, soul singers, hip-hop, 105–138 BPM with True Believer outlier at 80 BPM, Stories-era warmth and diversity — less folk-crossover more pop-house-country-soul blend, intimate verse energy building to festival chorus", "lyric_prompt": "Write a Stories-era Avicii song about a moment in life that becomes a defining story — an experience that shapes who you are. The emotional world of Stories: living fully, seizing the present, the wisdom of experiences lived. Verses should feel narrative and warm. The chorus should be a universal declaration about time, memory, or presence. Think of the lyric as something an older person would say to their younger self with deep affection and zero regret. Under 3:45."}, {"title": "AVĪCI (01) EP", "year": 2017, "style_prompt": "Late-era organic guitar-driven pop-house EP, 114–126 BPM, live instrumentation aesthetic — real guitar prominent, Vargas and Lagola warm Swedish production, less festival-focused than True and Stories, intimate organic scale, introspective and emotionally vulnerable subject matter, 2017 final-era Avicii sound before his death", "lyric_prompt": "Write an AVICI EP-era Avicii song in the emotional register of his final work: honest, vulnerable, searching. The EP was about friendship, shared loneliness, identity, and emotional openness. Choose one: (A) a song about a transformative friendship; (B) two lonely people finding each other; (C) a negotiation of roles and needs within a close bond. Verses feel intimate and personal. The chorus achieves emotional release. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "TIM", "year": 2019, "style_prompt": "Late-era posthumous melodic house, emotionally raw and vulnerable production completed by Vargas and Lagola, 120–126 BPM, Avicii's final vision — elements of psychedelia, organic warmth, more introspective than True or Stories, warm bittersweet production, all profits to Tim Bergling Foundation for mental health awareness", "lyric_prompt": "Write a TIM-era Avicii song in the emotional register of his final and most honest work. TIM was about needing help, finding love, seeking belonging, and confronting isolation. Choose one: (A) a cry for help that only comes out as a song; (B) the search for a place or person that feels like home; (C) the awareness of one's own fragility and the courage to admit it. The verses should feel personal and specific. The chorus should achieve the emotional release that the verses build toward. Under 3:45."}]}, {"id": "blink182", "name": "Blink-182", "genres": ["Pop-Punk", "Skate-Punk", "Emo", "Alternative Rock"], "era": "1992–2025", "color": "#ff4757", "bio": "Pop-punk pioneers. Travis Barker drumming engine. Tom DeLonge and Mark Hoppus dual vocal tag team spanning classic Enema of the State era through the 2023 Tom reunion album One More Time. No click tracks on the self-titled album — recorded in a rented mansion converted into a musical laboratory using vintage analog gear.", "producer_notes": "Jerry Finn (Enema, TOYPAJ) — super bright compressed production. Self-titled: vintage analog mansion sessions. Neighborhoods: Tom and Mark recording separately and merging digitally. One More Time (2023): most polished Blink production ever.", "songs": [{"title": "Pretty Little Girl", "album": "Neighborhoods", "year": 2011, "bpm": 140, "vibe": "Hip-hop crossover · Yelawolf feature", "dna": "Features Yelawolf — only the second time a Blink song had guest vocals. Modern pop-punk with electronic elements, pulsing synth bed. Travis Barker drumming bridges pop-punk and hip-hop. Melodic Tom DeLonge verse leading into a harder hip-hop bridge.", "style_prompt": "Modern pop-punk with hip-hop crossover elements, 140 BPM, clean melodic punk verses with pulsing electronic synth bed, Travis Barker-style aggressive precise drumming, distorted power chord rhythm guitar, melodic male tenor lead vocal, hip-hop rap section in bridge over drum track, modern polished production, punch and clarity in low end, singalong chorus with layered harmonies, suburban obsession energy", "lyric_prompt": "Write a modern pop-punk song about a guy who is completely fixated on a girl who is out of his league — or at least he thinks so. Melodic verses set the obsession scene: he sees her everywhere, she doesn't notice, he can't stop. The chorus is a punchy declaration of wanting her. The bridge should switch energy dramatically — a rapped or spoken section from a different voice describing her from the outside with specific swagger. Classic Blink tone: self-deprecating, lovesick, but more self-aware than teenage. Under 3:20."}, {"title": "Edging", "album": "One More Time...", "year": 2023, "bpm": 148, "vibe": "Reunion album anthem · Tom + Mark dual vocal", "dna": "The reunion album's defining statement. Fast, anthemic, Tom and Mark trading vocals on a song literally about the tension of almost reaching something. Most polished Blink production ever while still hitting like classic pop-punk. Enormous chorus. Travis's drumming at its most technically impressive.", "style_prompt": "Anthemic modern pop-punk, 148 BPM, dual male vocal trading verses — one higher melodic tenor, one deeper punk delivery, technically precise explosive drum fills, heavily distorted rhythm power chords, massive layered chorus with gang vocals, clean modern production with raw punk energy underneath, tension-and-release song structure, emotionally charged reunion energy, wide stereo mix, punchy bass", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast, anthemic pop-punk song built on the metaphor of being perpetually almost there — almost saying the right thing, almost getting back together, almost making it work — the feeling of prolonged emotional tension without release. The song should have two distinct voices alternating: one more melodic and searching, one more raw and direct. The chorus is the eruption of that tension — all the things almost said, finally half-said. The lyrics have double meaning throughout: the relationship tension and the band's own history of breakup and reunion. Under 3:15."}, {"title": "Mutt", "album": "Enema of the State", "year": 1999, "bpm": 181, "vibe": "Fast skate-punk · Classic era", "dna": "Classic Enema era — 181 BPM, blistering tempo, loud/fast California punk. Mark Hoppus lead vocal, sarcastic and self-deprecating. Jerry Finn production: super bright, compressed, slamming. Quintessential late-90s pop-punk aggression with tight melody.", "style_prompt": "Blistering late-90s pop-punk, 181 BPM, Mark Hoppus-style bass-forward vocal delivery, Jerry Finn-style super compressed bright production, power chord barrage, insanely fast drumming with snappy snare, no complex arrangements — speed and hooks, slightly sarcastic/self-deprecating male vocal, short under 2:30, loud and fast from the first second, singalong punk chorus, California skate-punk energy", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast, sarcastic pop-punk song from a guy who watches a girl he likes constantly date terrible, toxic guys — and he can't understand why she won't notice him instead. The tone is self-deprecating and slightly bitter but mostly just perplexed and annoyed. The chorus is a direct observation about the pattern. Short, fast, under 2:30. No emotional depth required — this is pure pop-punk frustration delivered at maximum BPM. Late 90s slang and attitude welcome."}, {"title": "Aliens Exist", "album": "Enema of the State", "year": 1999, "bpm": 188, "vibe": "Tom DeLonge UFO obsession in pop-punk form", "dna": "188 BPM — among Blink's fastest. Tom DeLonge lead vocal. Classic Enema production — Jerry Finn bright and punchy. The lyric is literally about believing in aliens and government cover-ups, delivered with full Tom DeLonge sincerity.", "style_prompt": "Blazing fast late-90s pop-punk, 188 BPM, Tom DeLonge-style nasally sincere tenor vocal — earnest not sarcastic, super bright compressed Jerry Finn production, blistering power chord drive, tight fast drumming, under 2:20, conspiracy/paranoia lyric delivered with absolute sincerity, singalong hook chorus, California punk guitar tone, no electronics — pure guitars bass drums", "lyric_prompt": "Write a blazing fast pop-punk song delivered with complete earnest sincerity about believing in aliens, government cover-ups, and things the authorities don't want you to know. The singer is not joking — he genuinely believes all of it and wants you to understand. The tone is not paranoid-angry but passionate and desperate to convince. The chorus is a declaration of belief. Include specific references to Area 51, black helicopters, unexplained lights. Under 2:20. This song should feel like the most sincere punk song about extraterrestrials ever written."}, {"title": "Ghost on the Dance Floor", "album": "Neighborhoods", "year": 2011, "bpm": 103, "vibe": "Gothic haunted atmosphere · Tom DeLonge lead", "dna": "103 BPM — one of their slower, more atmospheric tracks. The Neighborhoods album had Tom and Mark recording separately and digitally merging. Ghost on the Dance Floor is the album's most haunting track: electronic elements, post-rock atmosphere. Written about a deceased friend.", "style_prompt": "Atmospheric post-punk, 103 BPM, spacious reverb-heavy production, electronic synth bed under distorted guitars, haunting male tenor vocal with wide reverb — ethereal and ghostly, post-rock dynamics, grief and the supernatural as emotional core, dance floor imagery meets funeral atmosphere, wide stereo field, angular guitar lines, builds to emotional climax, Blink-182 meets Angels and Airwaves aesthetic", "lyric_prompt": "Write a haunting atmospheric pop-punk song about seeing someone who is gone — a friend who died — everywhere you go, especially in places they used to love. The singer can't stop sensing their presence, particularly on a dance floor or at a venue where they used to be together. The tone is grief filtered through the supernatural — not horror, but aching longing. The chorus is the central image: seeing their ghost in a specific place. Include the moment where the narrator realizes the ghost isn't real, and the crash of that realization. Under 4 minutes. Slow, atmospheric, devastating."}, {"title": "Even If She Falls", "album": "Neighborhoods", "year": 2011, "bpm": 145, "vibe": "Mark Hoppus lead · Faithful love anthem", "dna": "Mark Hoppus lead on this upbeat, earnest devotion anthem — a more mature take on love than classic Blink. More emotional sincerity than comedy, representing where the band had grown to by 2011.", "style_prompt": "Upbeat earnest pop-punk devotion anthem, 145 BPM, Mark Hoppus-style warm bass-forward delivery, bright layered production, distorted rhythm guitars, tight punchy drumming, emotionally sincere male vocal — no comedy, genuine love song in punk packaging, layered harmonies on chorus, full-bodied modern pop-punk production, devotion and loyalty as lyric core", "lyric_prompt": "Write a sincere, upbeat pop-punk devotion song about a guy who is committed to standing by someone he loves through anything — her failures, her worst days, her doubts about herself. The tone is mature and genuine — no jokes, no irony. Pop-punk packaging around real emotional commitment. The chorus is a direct declaration of unconditional presence. Include verses about specific ways she struggles and specific ways he shows up. Under 3:15."}, {"title": "Anthem Part Two", "album": "Take Off Your Pants and Jacket", "year": 2001, "bpm": 155, "vibe": "Anti-authoritarian youth anthem", "dna": "One of Blink's most politically charged moments — anti-authority, anti-conformity, rebellious youth energy. Fast, driving, gang-vocal chorus. Tom and Mark alternating. Simple, direct, loud. Pure Warped Tour anthemic energy.", "style_prompt": "Fast anti-authoritarian pop-punk anthem, 155 BPM, dual vocal trading verses, massive gang-vocal chorus screaming, driving power chords, Travis Barker relentless drumming, youth rebellion energy, simple direct lyrics — no subtlety, this is a fist-pump anthem, Warped Tour crowd energy, layered shouted backing vocals, under 2:45, aggressive bright production", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast, loud pop-punk youth rebellion anthem — a direct address to kids telling them to ignore authority figures, conform to nothing, make their own rules. The tone is earnest and angry rather than comedic. The chorus should be the kind of lyric 10,000 people scream at once with fists in the air. Include specific authority targets: parents, teachers, society's expectations. Two vocalists trading verses. Under 2:45. Loud. Fast. No nuance required."}, {"title": "All the Small Things", "album": "Enema of the State", "year": 1999, "bpm": 148, "vibe": "Pop-punk's defining MTV hit", "dna": "The song that put pop-punk on MTV. Tom DeLonge lead, Jerry Finn production at its most irresistible. The 'na na na' section. Super bright, clean, hook-forward. Structurally perfect — 2:47 of pure hook-delivery-hook.", "style_prompt": "Irresistibly catchy pop-punk, 148 BPM, super bright Jerry Finn-style compressed production, Tom DeLonge-style sincere tenor lead vocal, hooky singalong na-na-na section, short and perfectly structured under 2:50, romantic gesture lyrics delivered with complete earnestness, fast drumming with snappy snare, layered melodic guitar harmonics on lead, no fat — every second is a hook", "lyric_prompt": "Write a perfectly compact pop-punk love song celebrating the small, everyday things a person does for you — the kind of gestures that prove love without grand declarations. The lyric should catalogue specific small acts (leaving notes, saying goodnight, remembering things). The chorus is a hooky singalong declaration — include a 'na na na' or similar chantable section. Keep it under 2:50. Every line should be instantly singable. This is about perfecting the hook, not exploring emotion. The world's most irresistible simple love song."}, {"title": "The Rock Show", "album": "Take Off Your Pants and Jacket", "year": 2001, "bpm": 151, "vibe": "Classic Blink meet-at-a-show story", "dna": "Mark Hoppus lead vocal. Quintessential Blink narrative song — meets a girl at a rock show. Simple story at driving tempo. Quintessential TOYPAJ production — super punchy, fast, hooks everywhere.", "style_prompt": "Driving pop-punk narrative, 151 BPM, Mark Hoppus-style warm bass vocal lead, super punchy TOYPAJ-era production, fast clean guitar power chords, narrative storytelling verses building to hook explosion chorus, tight precise drumming, meet-at-a-concert atmosphere, under 3 minutes, bright and energetic throughout, singalong chorus with layered gang vocals", "lyric_prompt": "Write a driving pop-punk narrative song about meeting a girl at a rock show — she's cooler and more beautiful than anyone he's ever seen, he spends the whole show staring at her, finally talks to her, and is completely destroyed in the best way. The song should move like the story — fast, propulsive, specific details about the venue, the crowd, the songs playing. The chorus is the declaration of what she did to him in that one night. Under 3 minutes. Pure fun, no angst."}, {"title": "First Date", "album": "Take Off Your Pants and Jacket", "year": 2001, "bpm": 154, "vibe": "Pre-date anxiety played for laughs", "dna": "Tom DeLonge lead, fast, nervous energy perfectly matched by tempo. Quintessential Blink comedy-mixed-with-sincerity: the guy is genuinely nervous but the delivery is self-aware and funny.", "style_prompt": "Fast nervous-energy pop-punk, 154 BPM, Tom DeLonge-style sincere tenor lead, super bright punchy production, driving power chord rhythm, first-date jitters translated into tempo, funny-but-sincere vocal delivery, under 2:30, comedic self-awareness with genuine underlying feeling, singalong chorus, TOYPAJ-era Blink brightness and speed", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast, funny pop-punk song from a guy preparing for and going on a first date — the nervous energy, the overthinking, the awkward moments, and the genuine hopefulness underneath it all. The humor comes from the specific ridiculous things he worries about. The chorus is sincere: underneath all the nerves, he really likes her. Under 2:30. This should make someone laugh and feel tender at the same time."}, {"title": "Carousel", "album": "Buddha EP / Cheshire Cat", "year": 1994, "bpm": 184, "vibe": "Early Blink chaos · Mark lead", "dna": "One of the earliest Blink recordings — raw, chaotic, Mark Hoppus lead vocal. Pre-Jerry Finn production, lo-fi and aggressive. Classic early San Diego skatepunk sound.", "style_prompt": "Raw early skate-punk, 184 BPM, lo-fi garage production — sloppy and perfect, Mark Hoppus-style nasal bass vocal lead, simple two-chord power chord aggression, chaotic drum fills everywhere, under 2 minutes, no polished production — raw and loud, early 90s San Diego punk energy, trebly guitar tone, genuine teenage urgency", "lyric_prompt": "Write a raw, chaotic early skate-punk song — simple, fast, barely under control. The theme is circular frustration: being stuck in the same patterns, the same mistakes, going around and around like a carousel. The lyrics should feel like a teenager wrote them — genuine, unpolished, angry at nothing specific but angry at everything. Under 1:45. No sophistication required. Just urgency, volume, and teenage feeling."}, {"title": "Turpentine", "album": "One More Time...", "year": 2023, "bpm": 130, "vibe": "Emotional reunion-era depth", "dna": "From the 2023 reunion album — one of the deeper, more emotionally raw cuts. More angular, less poppy than classic Blink. The band processing Travis's recovery, Tom's return, and years of separation.", "style_prompt": "Modern emotionally heavy pop-punk, 130 BPM, more angular production than classic Blink, introspective male vocals alternating between controlled and raw, heavier guitar distortion with less brightness, mid-tempo with emotional weight, modern production clarity, reunion and survival themes, processing loss and return, layered harmonies, under 3:30, less comedy more raw vulnerability", "lyric_prompt": "Write a raw, emotionally heavy pop-punk song about surviving something that nearly destroyed you — a friendship, a near-death, a long estrangement — and finding your way back to it. The tone is older and heavier than classic Blink, the comedy is gone. What remains is gratitude filtered through pain. The chorus is about what's left when turpentine burns everything away — the essential thing that couldn't be destroyed. Under 3:30. The most emotionally honest Blink song in the set."}, {"title": "One Night Stand", "album": "Dogs Eating Dogs EP", "year": 2012, "bpm": 150, "vibe": "Post-hiatus · darker adult tone", "dna": "From the post-reunion Dogs Eating Dogs EP. Tom DeLonge lead with a slightly darker, more confessional tone. Adult subject matter — the complicated morning-after feelings. Shows the band's maturation.", "style_prompt": "Post-hiatus Blink pop-punk, 150 BPM, Tom DeLonge-style sincere tenor lead — slightly darker than Enema era, adult subject matter in punk packaging, distorted rhythm guitars with some atmospheric texture, Travis Barker precise driving drumming, confessional morning-after emotional core, under 3 minutes, still melodic and punchy but with more emotional weight than classic Blink", "lyric_prompt": "Write a pop-punk song about the complicated feeling after a one-night stand — not bragging, not regret exactly, but the specific discomfort of lying next to a stranger and wondering how you got here. The verses are honest and specific about the morning after. The chorus is the complicated emotional statement — wanting more but knowing this wasn't meant to be more. Adult Blink tone: still punchy and melodic but genuinely honest. Under 3 minutes."}, {"title": "Story of a Lonely Guy", "album": "Take Off Your Pants and Jacket", "year": 2001, "bpm": 127, "vibe": "Mark Hoppus lead · emotionally vulnerable", "dna": "Mark Hoppus lead, slightly slower than typical TOYPAJ. One of Blink's more emotionally direct songs — genuine loneliness and romantic failure, not played for laughs.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo earnest pop-punk, 127 BPM, Mark Hoppus-style warm emotionally direct bass vocal, TOYPAJ production slightly restrained for emotional space, distorted rhythm guitar, sincere loneliness as lyric core — no comedy, chorus builds to emotional release, under 3 minutes, genuine heartache in pop-punk packaging, harmonies adding warmth on chorus", "lyric_prompt": "Write a sincere, emotionally direct pop-punk song about genuine loneliness — not funny, not ironic. A guy who keeps falling for people who don't love him back, who spends Friday nights alone, who watches others connect effortlessly while he can't. The tone is honest without being self-pitying. The chorus is a direct statement of the loneliness. The bridge is the moment he asks what's wrong with him — and leaves it unanswered. Under 3 minutes."}, {"title": "Stay Together for the Kids", "album": "Take Off Your Pants and Jacket", "year": 2001, "bpm": 142, "vibe": "Blink's most emotionally serious pre-hiatus song", "dna": "Tom DeLonge lead. Written about parents staying in failing marriages for children's sake — and the damage that does. Builds from a quiet intro to an explosive climax. Unique dynamic arc for pre-hiatus Blink.", "style_prompt": "Emotionally serious pop-punk with dynamic structure, 142 BPM, quiet restrained verse building to explosive distorted climax, Tom DeLonge-style earnest tenor lead — no comedy, genuine anger and pain, TOYPAJ production at its most dynamic, divorce and childhood damage as lyric core, builds from near acoustic to full band explosion, under 3:30, the most emotionally heavy pre-hiatus Blink energy", "lyric_prompt": "Write a pop-punk song from the perspective of a child or teenager watching their parents' failing marriage — seeing through the performance of 'staying together for the kids' and knowing it's making everything worse, not better. The anger is directed at the situation, not at the parents specifically — just at the lie of pretending. The song builds from quiet observation to an explosive chorus of frustration. Include specific domestic images: empty dinners, separate rooms, the performance of normalcy. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "Feeling This", "album": "Blink-182 (Self-Titled)", "year": 2003, "bpm": 173, "vibe": "Tom and Mark alternating · mature production", "dna": "Self-titled album — vintage analog mansion sessions. Flagship single. Tom and Mark alternating vocals. 173 BPM, explosive, most technically advanced Blink production up to that point. Two distinct narrative voices.", "style_prompt": "Explosive mature pop-punk, 173 BPM, two distinct male vocal personalities alternating — one punchy and direct, one melodic and earnest, vintage analog production warmth with modern energy, technically advanced drumming with syncopated fills, dual narrative lyric structure, layered guitar textures, under 3 minutes, the most sonically sophisticated Blink energy, genuine emotional complexity", "lyric_prompt": "Write a pop-punk song with two distinct vocal/lyric narratives that intertwine: Voice 1 tells the physical, immediate story of a night together — specific, direct, slightly detached. Voice 2 tells the emotional interior — what's actually being felt, the genuine connection underneath. The two voices should meet and harmonize in the chorus, where both truths land simultaneously. The song should feel like two sides of the same experience. Under 3 minutes. Structurally adventurous."}, {"title": "I Miss You", "album": "Blink-182 (Self-Titled)", "year": 2003, "bpm": 110, "vibe": "Gothic Cure-influenced ballad · 1B+ Spotify streams", "dna": "All acoustic instruments: piano, cello, acoustic bass guitar, brushstroked hip-hop groove. Directly inspired by The Cure's The Love Cats. Over one billion Spotify streams. DeLonge: the song is about vulnerability and not wanting someone to waste their time on you.", "style_prompt": "Gothic acoustic pop-punk ballad, 110 BPM, Cure-influenced dark romanticism, acoustic instruments only — piano, cello, acoustic bass, brushstroke hip-hop drum groove, male tenor vocal in wide reverb — earnest and slightly theatrical, Tom and Mark alternating narrative voices, haunted mansion atmosphere, B major melancholy, vulnerability and pre-emptive heartbreak as lyric core, under 3:50, both beautiful and aching", "lyric_prompt": "Write a gothic acoustic ballad about the pre-emptive heartbreak of loving someone while believing they've already mentally left — telling them 'don't waste your time on me, you've already given up on me in your head.' The tone is both vulnerable and somewhat theatrical — more Tim Burton than emo. The instrumentation is acoustic and orchestral, not punk. Include Halloween/gothic imagery that serves the emotional metaphor without being campy. Two vocal perspectives alternating. The most emotionally devastating song in the Blink catalog. Under 3:50."}, {"title": "Wishing Well", "album": "Neighborhoods", "year": 2011, "bpm": 99, "vibe": "Atmospheric slow-burn · Mark Hoppus lead", "dna": "99 BPM — among the slowest in their catalog. Mark Hoppus lead in atmospheric, post-rock territory. Neighborhoods era spacious, reverb-driven sound.", "style_prompt": "Atmospheric slow pop-punk, 99 BPM, spacious reverb-heavy Neighborhoods production, Mark Hoppus warm contemplative vocal, post-rock guitar textures, wide stereo field, emotional wishing and longing as core, builds slowly to full-band climax, under 4 minutes, more atmosphere than aggression, wistful and aching rather than angry", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow, atmospheric pop-punk song about wanting something you know you can't have — not a person, but a version of the past, or a version of yourself, or a second chance at something specific that's already gone. The wishing-well metaphor: you keep making the wish, knowing it won't be granted. The tone is wistful and slow — no aggression. The chorus is the wish itself, stated plainly. Under 4 minutes. Let it breathe."}, {"title": "Reckless Abandon", "album": "Take Off Your Pants and Jacket", "year": 2001, "bpm": 210, "vibe": "Fastest Blink song · pure chaos", "dna": "Among Blink's fastest songs ever. Tom DeLonge lead. A song that essentially IS its title: no brakes, no structure, just velocity. Classic Blink adolescent-freedom energy at its rawest.", "style_prompt": "Maximum speed pop-punk, 210 BPM or faster, absolute fastest possible tempo, Tom DeLonge barely-controlled yelling lead vocal, drums sounding like a car crash at speed, wall of distorted power chords, under 1:45, no subtlety — pure velocity, adolescent freedom-and-chaos energy, sounds like it could fall apart at any second but doesn't, Warped Tour mosh pit energy", "lyric_prompt": "Write the fastest, most chaotic pop-punk song possible — a celebration of doing stupid things at high speed and not caring about consequences. Driving too fast, staying out all night, breaking things, laughing at everything. The song itself should feel like it's barely under control. No emotional depth. No metaphors. Pure adolescent reckless joy. Under 1:45. If it's longer than 1:45 it's too slow."}]}, {"id": "greenday", "name": "Green Day", "genres": ["Punk Rock", "Pop-Punk", "Punk Opera", "Alternative Rock"], "era": "1987–2025", "color": "#a8e063", "bio": "Billie Joe Armstrong, Mike Dirnt, Tré Cool. Rob Cavallo produced their major-label run from Dookie through American Idiot. Known for power chords combined with strong pop melodic sensibility. American Idiot is a punk rock opera following Jesus of Suburbia — expressing the disillusionment of a generation shaped by 9/11 and the Iraq War.", "producer_notes": "Rob Cavallo (Dookie through 21st Century Breakdown) — enormous snare, everything sounds bigger than it should be. Butch Vig produced 21st Century Breakdown.", "songs": [{"title": "Jesus of Suburbia", "album": "American Idiot", "year": 2004, "bpm": "Multi-tempo 80–184", "vibe": "9-minute 5-movement punk opera", "dna": "9 minutes 8 seconds, five distinct movements. Armstrong wrote it as an attempt at the Bohemian Rhapsody of the future. The opening bars evoke David Bowie's Moonage Daydream. Each section has its own distinct tempo, feel, and emotional register.", "style_prompt": "Multi-movement punk rock opera, 5 distinct sections at varying tempos 80–184 BPM, opens with sparse acoustic guitar-voice call-and-response, builds through melodic storytelling to full punk explosion, Bowie-influenced glam rock elements under punk structure, Billie Joe Armstrong style sneer-to-anthem vocal arc, Rob Cavallo production clarity, suburban alienation narrative, cinematic scope in punk packaging, 7–9 minute runtime permitted", "lyric_prompt": "Write a multi-movement punk rock epic — five distinct sections that tell a complete story arc. A suburban teenager: I. Describes his miserable town and diet of media and medication — angry, staccato, spoken-word intro; II. Announces he's leaving — melodic and searching; III. Arrives in the city and finds it just as hollow — punk explosion; IV. Considers what he's lost and what he's become — quieter reflection; V. A defiant declaration that he owns his alienation — full-band outro. Total runtime 7–9 minutes. Each section should feel like a different song that connects to the same story."}, {"title": "American Idiot", "album": "American Idiot", "year": 2004, "bpm": 184, "vibe": "Defining protest anthem of the 2000s", "dna": "Released two months before George W. Bush was reelected. 184 BPM, 2:54 of pure compressed fury. The palm-muted opening guitar riff is instantly recognizable. Targets media manipulation, jingoism, and the redneck agenda.", "style_prompt": "Blazing protest punk anthem, 184 BPM, opening palm-muted guitar riff under sneering political vocal, enormous Rob Cavallo production — everything sounds bigger than it should, Billie Joe Armstrong sneer-to-scream vocal arc, under 3 minutes, no-fat punk compression, media manipulation and political outrage as lyric core, freight-train momentum, gang-vocal chorus screamed, anti-authoritarian fury delivered with pop precision", "lyric_prompt": "Write a blazing 184 BPM protest punk anthem — the defining political statement of a disillusioned generation. Target: media manipulation, manufactured patriotism, political leaders who treat the public as idiots to be managed. The tone is contemptuous of conformity and blind nationalism. The chorus is a screamed rejection — refusing to be part of the machine. Include the word 'idiot' used to describe both the powerful and the compliant. Under 3 minutes. Maximum compression, maximum fury. Every word loaded."}, {"title": "Wake Me Up When September Ends", "album": "American Idiot", "year": 2004, "bpm": 104, "vibe": "Grief ballad · Armstrong's father's death", "dna": "Written about Armstrong's father, who died of cancer when Billie was 10. Starts with clean acoustic guitar, builds through two verse-chorus cycles, culminates in full electric climax, returns to acoustic. Rob Cavallo lets the dynamic do the work.", "style_prompt": "Dynamic grief ballad, 104 BPM, opens with clean acoustic guitar — delicate and exposed, male vocal raw with loss, builds through two cycles adding electric guitar and drums, culminates in full-band electric explosion at the climax, then strips back to acoustic close, Rob Cavallo quiet-loud-quiet production arc, genuine grief not performed grief, autumn and loss imagery, under 4:45, the most emotionally devastating Green Day energy", "lyric_prompt": "Write a grief ballad about losing a parent young — not dramatized or poeticized, just raw and honest. September as the month of the loss. The song asks to be allowed to skip the month entirely — to sleep through the anniversary of losing them. The emotional arc: quiet description of the ongoing loss → building toward the anniversary → full emotional release at the climax → quiet return to the beginning. Use autumn imagery organically. The most restrained and most devastating moment should be the last line. Under 4:45."}, {"title": "Good Riddance (Time of Your Life)", "album": "Nimrod", "year": 1997, "bpm": 84, "vibe": "Accidental anthem · acoustic only", "dna": "Written as an angry breakup song, misread as a sentimental anthem — Armstrong decided to let the misreading stand. Acoustic guitar only with subtle violin. 2:33. Deceptively simple: three chords, one perspective. Played at both graduations and funerals.", "style_prompt": "Sparse acoustic punk ballad, 84 BPM, acoustic guitar only with subtle violin, conversational male vocal — no performance, just direct honest delivery, under 2:40, bittersweet ambiguity between anger and sentimentality, three-chord simplicity, the most universally resonant energy possible, graduation-and-goodbye atmosphere, nothing wasted — every word essential", "lyric_prompt": "Write a sparse acoustic song with radical ambiguity — it can be read as an angry send-off or a bittersweet farewell, and both readings are equally valid. The central lyric question should be about unpredictability and choices made at crossroads. The tone is direct, conversational, not sentimental in the traditional way — more resigned acceptance. Under 2:40. Three chords. No fat. The most deceptively simple song in the set — every single word must earn its place. This should be played at both breakups and graduations."}, {"title": "Basket Case", "album": "Dookie", "year": 1994, "bpm": 186, "vibe": "Anxiety as pop-punk · the Dookie breakthrough", "dna": "Written by Armstrong about his anxiety disorder before he was diagnosed. The result is anxiety portrayed from the inside: fast, chaotic, self-aware but unable to stop. Rob Cavallo Dookie production: bright, fast, enormous snare.", "style_prompt": "Anxiety-driven Dookie-era punk, 186 BPM, Rob Cavallo bright enormous-snare production, vocal delivery rushed and anxious in verses — the words come too fast, chorus erupts into desperate naming, under 3 minutes, guitar tone bright and trebly, bass prominent, anxiety from the inside as lyric structure — self-aware but unable to stop, the most energetically anxious Green Day energy", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast punk song about anxiety from the inside — not describing anxiety from outside but the experience of living in it. The verses should feel rushed, the thoughts tumbling over each other. The chorus is the desperate attempt to name what's happening: 'am I paranoid or am I just anxious / am I crazy or is this just Tuesday?' The self-awareness doesn't help — the narrator knows what's happening and can't stop it. Under 2:45. Written by someone who didn't have the diagnosis yet, just the experience."}, {"title": "Holiday", "album": "American Idiot", "year": 2004, "bpm": 117, "vibe": "Anti-war anthem · marching energy", "dna": "The march-rhythm opening. Anti-war, anti-Bush, anti-media compliance. The production has a military snare quality — the beat of war repurposed as protest. The breakdown 'This is the dawning of the rest of our lives' is the most anthemic moment.", "style_prompt": "Anti-war protest punk with military march energy, 117 BPM marching tempo, snare-driven rhythm suggesting a march turned protest, Billie Joe Armstrong contemptuous sneering vocal, Rob Cavallo enormous production, political outrage at war and media compliance, massive singalong breakdown section, under 3:50, driving relentless energy, punk power chords over march beat, crowd-participation anthem", "lyric_prompt": "Write a punk anthem that uses the word 'holiday' sarcastically — a holiday from reality, from truth, from having to think about what your government is doing in your name. The song targets war, propaganda, blind patriotism. The tone is furious contempt, not sad resignation. Include a breakdown section that shifts from verse cynicism to a massive crowd-participation moment about resistance and solidarity. The military march rhythm should be felt in the lyric cadence. Under 3:50."}, {"title": "21 Guns", "album": "21st Century Breakdown", "year": 2009, "bpm": 69, "vibe": "Slowest Green Day hit · Butch Vig production", "dna": "From 21st Century Breakdown, produced by Butch Vig. 69 BPM — Green Day's slowest major single. Piano opens the track. Builds to a full-band stadium rock climax. Armstrong's vocal is at its most naked and powerful.", "style_prompt": "Slow-build stadium punk ballad, 69 BPM, opens with solo piano — exposed and fragile, Billie Joe Armstrong-style raw tenor builds from intimate to enormous, Butch Vig production adding weight and scale, full-band climax with massive singalong chorus, military honor imagery reframed as personal sacrifice, under 5:30, the most dynamically ambitious Green Day energy, surrender as the theme", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow-build stadium punk ballad about surrender — not defeat, but the conscious, dignified choice to lay down what you've been fighting for because the fight has cost too much. The 21-gun salute as central metaphor: honoring what's being let go. The song should move from intimate piano confession to full-band cathartic release. The central question: when does fighting for something become destroying it? The chorus is the moment of beautiful surrender — arms open, white flag raised with dignity. Under 5:30. The biggest, slowest, most cinematic song in the set."}]}, {"id": "ratm", "name": "Rage Against the Machine", "genres": ["Rap-Metal", "Funk-Metal", "Hip-Hop", "Alternative Metal", "Hardcore"], "era": "1991–2011", "color": "#ffa502", "bio": "Tom Morello, Zack de la Rocha, Tim Commerford, Brad Wilk. Formed in Los Angeles 1991. None of their albums were recorded with a click track — all have natural tempo drift, and the true mode across the catalog sits around 84–90 BPM, making them distinctly slow and heavy for rock. Morello identifies as a DJ using his guitar — using the kill switch rhythmically, imitating record scratching, employing a DigiTech Whammy pedal. De la Rocha's vocal style combines controlled hip-hop verse delivery with explosive screamed sloganeering. Inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2023. Won Grammy Awards for Best Metal Performance (Tire Me) and Best Hard Rock Performance (Guerrilla Radio).", "producer_notes": "Debut (1992): self-produced, GGGarth Richardson, Sound City Van Nuys CA. Evil Empire (1996): Brendan O'Brien, Cole Rehearsal Studios Hollywood. Battle of Los Angeles (1999): Brendan O'Brien, tightest production. Renegades (2000): Rick Rubin, covers album, brickwalled mastering. All albums: 'No samples, keyboards or synthesizers used in the making of this record.' Suno note: frame political content as anti-authoritarian rather than explicitly radical to avoid content filters.", "songs": [{"title": "Bombtrack", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 76, "vibe": "Album opener · Tim Commerford bass riffs · F# minor · Che Guevara artwork", "dna": "Opens the debut album. Riffs composed by Tim Commerford. One of three debut tracks in F# with Know Your Enemy and Fistful of Steel. Opens with a solo guitar riff around 86 BPM before the full band slows it dramatically — classic RATM no-click-track tempo drift. Third single; highest Netherlands chart position at number 8. Single artwork featured Korda's iconic Che Guevara photograph. Lyric targets landlords and capitalist property exploitation.", "style_prompt": "Slow heavy funk-metal, 76 BPM natural tempo drift, Tim Commerford bass-composed riff opening, Morello angular guitar stabs, Brad Wilk thunderous pocket, de la Rocha controlled-then-explosive rap vocal, F# minor, no synthesizers — all live instruments, landlord exploitation lyric, debut Sound City GGGarth production", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow heavy rap-metal song targeting economic exploitation — specifically landlords, corporate property ownership, and the class relationship between those who own land and those who must pay to exist. Verses are controlled and precise. The chorus is a declaration that the system will burn — stated with certainty, not threat. Include fire and destruction as metaphors for systemic collapse. De la Rocha style: controlled rap verses building to screamed sloganeering. Under 4:15."}, {"title": "Killing in the Name", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 86, "vibe": "UK Christmas #1 (2009) · Whammy pedal solo · escalating refusal climax · institutional racism", "dna": "Morello used the DigiTech Whammy pedal on the solo and Ibanez DFL Flanger on the intro. One of the most cathartic rock recordings ever — the closing escalation of 'Fuck you I won't do what you tell me' building from spoken whisper to full scream. UK Christmas #1 in 2009 via Facebook campaign. Targets institutional racism and police brutality. Lyrics were deliberately omitted from the album booklet.", "style_prompt": "Slow heavy groove rap-metal, 86 BPM, flanger-textured opening riff, DigiTech Whammy guitar solo, Brad Wilk thunderous slow pocket, escalating closing section — defiant refusal phrase building from spoken to absolute full-volume scream, institutional racism lyric, debut raw production, most cathartic climax structure, under 5:15", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow heavy rap-metal song about institutional power doing harm in the name of authority. The verses name this contradiction with controlled precise anger. The song must end with an escalating refusal — a single defiant phrase repeated, starting quiet and spoken, building to absolute full-volume scream. This escalation IS the emotional point. The refusal to comply is the revolutionary act. Under 5:15."}, {"title": "Take the Power Back", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 105, "vibe": "Eurocentric education system critique · jazz-influenced groove · Morello whammy pitch dives", "dna": "Targets American education — specifically Eurocentric curricula erasing history. Most musically complex debut track. The groove has a jazz-influenced looseness. Morello uses dramatic pitch-dive whammy effects during the breakdown. De la Rocha's verse delivery is the most rhythmically hip-hop-influenced on the album. The breakdown features Morello's most jazz-guitar-adjacent playing.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo funk-metal with jazz groove, 105 BPM, complex syncopated rhythm, Morello pitch-dive whammy drops in breakdown, Brad Wilk jazz-influenced loose pocket, de la Rocha hip-hop verse cadence, education-system-erasure lyric, debut Sound City production, most rhythmically sophisticated debut track, under 5:35", "lyric_prompt": "Write a funk-metal song targeting the education system — specifically the erasure of non-Western history and the whitewashing of colonial history in schools. The verses catalogue what is taught versus what is omitted. The chorus is a call to reclaim knowledge. Include the idea that textbooks themselves are a form of control. Rhythmically complex — hip-hop cadence, not simple rock meter. Under 5:35."}, {"title": "Settle for Nothing", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 100, "vibe": "More personal than political · refusing diminished existence · slower introspective groove", "dna": "More introspective than the surrounding debut tracks — about the individual refusing to accept a diminished life rather than targeting a specific system. Features one of Morello's most controlled debut performances. The contrast of controlled verses and explosive chorus previews mature RATM structural approach.", "style_prompt": "Grinding mid-tempo rap-metal, 100 BPM, Morello controlled restraint building to explosions, Brad Wilk slow heavy pocket, de la Rocha personal-alienation lyric — individual refusing diminished existence, quiet-loud dynamic arc, debut Sound City production, under 4:47", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo rap-metal song about the personal refusal to accept a diminished, compromised existence — refusing to want less than you deserve. More personal than political: the narrator's interior experience of alienation and the systems that demand compliance. The chorus is the refusal — a declaration of not settling. Under 4:47."}, {"title": "Bullet in the Head", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 88, "vibe": "Cable-tap guitar effect · media lobotomy metaphor · industrial clicking percussion texture", "dna": "Morello created the signature guitar effect by tapping a pickup with the guitar's unplugged cable connector — generating industrial clicking percussion woven through the track. Targets media hypnosis — television as a weapon destroying critical thought. The cable-tap technique became one of his signature studio discoveries.", "style_prompt": "Heavy aggressive debut rap-metal, 88 BPM, cable-tap pickup percussive industrial clicking texture woven through groove, Brad Wilk relentless heavy pocket, de la Rocha rapid warning-delivery verses, media-hypnosis lyric, debut Sound City production, warning chorus hook, under 5 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a heavy rap-metal song about media as a weapon of mass distraction — entertainment designed to keep people passive and manageable. Passive consumption as a self-inflicted wound. The verses name specific distraction mechanisms with precision. The chorus is a warning about what this entertainment is doing to your brain. Anger at both the system that designs the distraction and the willingness to accept it. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Know Your Enemy", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 112, "vibe": "Fast declarative · F# with Bombtrack and Fistful of Steel · Malcolm X political lineage", "dna": "One of the faster debut tracks at 112 BPM. F# key like Bombtrack and Fistful of Steel. Lyric draws directly from Malcolm X's political consciousness — identifying the true enemy as the capitalist system rather than other oppressed people. De la Rocha's most explicitly political debut performance.", "style_prompt": "Fast-aggressive debut rap-metal, 112 BPM, F# minor, tight rhythm lock, Morello angular riff attack, de la Rocha confident declarative delivery naming enemies precisely, Black power political consciousness lyric, Sound City production, under 5 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast rap-metal song built entirely on the concept of knowing your enemy — identifying true systems of oppression rather than blaming the wrong targets. The verses name specific enemies: the system, ideology, institutions — not other oppressed people. The chorus is the demand: know your enemy. Include the importance of reading, historical consciousness, and understanding power. Confident and instructional, not paranoid. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Wake Up", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 85, "vibe": "The Matrix closing track · Ibanez DFL Flanger intro · political awakening anthem", "dna": "Famous for ending The Matrix (1999). The Ibanez DFL Flanger creates the distinctive swirling guitar intro texture. Builds through repeated escalation to de la Rocha's screamed finale. About political consciousness — waking up to the true nature of power. The song that plays as Neo realizes the truth of his world.", "style_prompt": "Heavy hypnotic rap-metal, 85 BPM, slow flanger-sweep guitar intro building to slinky funk-metal verse riff, conversational political hip-hop verses, Brad Wilk thunderous groove, building escalation to screamed sloganeering climax, political awakening lyric, debut Sound City production, under 6 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow hypnotic rap-metal song about political awakening — the moment someone realizes the systems around them are not neutral but designed. Controlled rhyming verses naming what is hidden. Energy builds through the song. The climax is a repeated screamed call for people to open their eyes. The tone is enraged and certain — awareness itself is a revolutionary act. Under 6 minutes."}, {"title": "Fistful of Steel", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 157, "vibe": "Fastest debut track · whammy dive-bombs · most structurally experimental debut song", "dna": "The fastest debut track at 157 BPM. Third F# song with Bombtrack and Know Your Enemy. Features Morello's most experimental debut guitar work — dramatic whammy dive-bombs and extended techniques. Structurally the most unusual debut track, with dramatically shifting sections. Less overtly political — more oblique and experimental.", "style_prompt": "Fast experimental debut rap-metal, 157 BPM, F# key, Morello dramatic whammy dive-bombs throughout, Brad Wilk driving fast pocket, de la Rocha oblique experimental lyric, most structurally unusual debut track, Sound City production, high energy, extended guitar technique showcase, under 5:30", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast oblique rap-metal song — more imagistic and abstract than typical, less direct sloganeering. Tone is aggressive and urgent but visceral and experiential rather than programmatic. Steel, force, physical power as metaphors for collective resistance. Structure should feel unpredictable — shifting sections with different energies. Under 5:30. RATM at their most experimental."}, {"title": "Township Rebellion", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 131, "vibe": "South African township uprisings · Tim Commerford bass showcase · upbeat debut tempo", "dna": "References South African apartheid-era township uprisings. One of the more upbeat debut tracks at 131 BPM. Features Commerford's most prominent bass work on the album. Draws on the history of Black South African resistance and connects it to American systemic racism. The faster tempo gives more propulsive urgency.", "style_prompt": "Upbeat heavy rap-metal, 131 BPM, Tim Commerford prominent bass groove, Morello tight chord work, Brad Wilk driving faster pocket, de la Rocha urgent delivery, South African township resistance and US systemic racism connections, debut Sound City production, under 5:24", "lyric_prompt": "Write an upbeat rap-metal song about collective uprising — drawing connections between different historical moments of oppressed people fighting back. Verses catalogue the conditions that create uprising. The chorus is the uprising itself — collective, defiant, unstoppable. Under 5:24."}, {"title": "Freedom", "album": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "bpm": 98, "vibe": "Debut closer · Leonard Peltier dedication · Morello abstract noise outro · hopeful fury", "dna": "Closes the debut. Dedicated to Leonard Peltier, Native American activist imprisoned since 1977 whom RATM campaigned to free. Builds from quiet intro to intense climax. De la Rocha screams 'freedom' repeatedly at the peak. The outro features abstract Morello noise guitar dissolving the song. Their most hopeful-while-furious statement.", "style_prompt": "Debut-era political rap-metal, 98 BPM, quiet textured intro building to full-band heavy groove, controlled verses building to screamed freedom-word climax, dedication to specific political prisoner, Morello abstract noise outro dissolving into silence, Sound City production, hopeful fury, under 6 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a rap-metal song dedicated to a specific political prisoner whose story illustrates a systemic wrong. Verses tell their story with precision. The song builds to a climax repeating the word 'freedom' with increasing fury — not platitude but demand. End with dissolving abstract outro. Under 6 minutes. Most hopeful-while-furious in the set."}, {"title": "People of the Sun", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 93, "vibe": "Evil Empire opener · Zapatista uprising tribute · choppy rhythmic riff", "dna": "Opens Evil Empire. Written in tribute to the Zapatista uprising in Chiapas, Mexico, which began January 1, 1994. RATM's declaration of support for indigenous Mexican resistance against NAFTA. Brendan O'Brien production — tighter and more aggressive than the debut. Nominated for Grammy Best Hard Rock Performance.", "style_prompt": "Opening aggressive rap-metal, 93 BPM, choppy rhythmic Morello guitar riff, tight O'Brien production, de la Rocha passionate indigenous rights delivery, Zapatista uprising tribute, Evil Empire opener energy, Brad Wilk tight pocket, heavier than debut, under 3 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast aggressive rap-metal song in tribute to indigenous resistance — the uprising of people dispossessed of land and rights by economic agreements and colonial systems. Historically specific: name the place, what was taken, who did the taking. The chorus is a declaration of defiance and solidarity. Fiercely proud and certain. Under 3 minutes."}, {"title": "Bulls on Parade", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 83, "vibe": "Guitar kill-switch scratch solo · minimal riff · military industrial complex · Grammy nominee", "dna": "Morello uses the guitar's pickup selector as a kill switch to imitate record scratching near the end. Ingeniously minimal riff. Perhaps the finest RATM sonic Molotov cocktail. Grammy nominated Best Hard Rock Performance. Targets the military-industrial complex. Hypnotic locked groove.", "style_prompt": "Minimal-riff funk-metal, 83 BPM, hypnotically spare guitar riff, Brad Wilk thunderous groove, de la Rocha rapid-fire political rhyming, guitar kill-switch scratch solo simulating turntable, military-industrial complex lyric, Evil Empire O'Brien production, under 3:50, groove carries everything", "lyric_prompt": "Write a funk-metal song targeting the military-industrial complex — weapons over food. Name the hypocrisy: leaders claiming family values while funding death. Precise indictments over hypnotic minimal groove. The chorus is a single overwhelming image of what the machine produces. Include 'weapons not food' or equivalent. Under 3:50. The groove feels like a march to the guillotine."}, {"title": "Vietnow", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 107, "vibe": "Vietnam War as propaganda template · right-wing radio critique · mid-tempo complex groove", "dna": "Targets right-wing talk radio and corporate media. The title combines Vietnam and now — arguing that media propaganda used during Vietnam continues and has intensified. Mid-tempo with a forward-pushing groove. Features Morello's most controlled rhythm work on Evil Empire.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo political rap-metal, 107 BPM, forward-pushing groove, Morello controlled rhythm riff, Brad Wilk steady heavy pocket, de la Rocha media-propaganda critique, Vietnam-as-template-for-current-media-control lyric, Evil Empire O'Brien production, under 4:30", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo rap-metal song about media control and propaganda — how wartime media manipulation became permanent corporate operating mode. The verses catalogue specific propaganda techniques: framing, omission, manufactured consent. The chorus is a demand to see through the noise. Include the idea that the war abroad and the war on your mind are run by the same people. Under 4:30."}, {"title": "Revolver", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 138, "vibe": "Fastest Evil Empire track · firearm-as-state-power metaphor · breathless aggression", "dna": "Fastest Evil Empire track at 138 BPM. The revolver as metaphor for state power and the monopoly on violence. Features Morello's most aggressive riff performance on Evil Empire. Almost breathlessly paced — unusual for the album's typically slow-burn approach.", "style_prompt": "Fast aggressive rap-metal, 138 BPM, fastest Evil Empire track, Morello aggressive high-energy riff, Brad Wilk driving fast pocket, de la Rocha firearm-power-metaphor lyric, O'Brien tight production, relentless momentum, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast rap-metal song using a firearm as an extended metaphor for state power — who holds the means of violence controls everything. The verses explore how this power functions: who has it, who doesn't, what happens to those who challenge it. The chorus is the confrontation of that power relationship. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Snakecharmer", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 97, "vibe": "Corporate seduction and hypnosis · sinuous groove mirroring content · Commerford bass showcase", "dna": "The snakecharmer as metaphor for corporate and political manipulation — controlling by seduction and hypnosis. The groove has a sinuous, hypnotic quality mirroring the content. Features Commerford's most prominent Evil Empire bass work.", "style_prompt": "Thick heavy rap-metal, 97 BPM, sinuous hypnotic groove mirroring seduction lyric, Tim Commerford prominent bass, Morello dark riff, Brad Wilk heavy locked pocket, corporate-manipulation-as-seduction lyric, Evil Empire O'Brien production, under 5 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a heavy rap-metal song about the seductive face of power — corporations, politicians, and media using charm and false promises to manipulate rather than brute force. You watch the snake and forget you're being bitten. The verses describe specific seduction techniques. The chorus is the moment of recognizing the manipulation. The groove should feel as hypnotic as the content. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Tire Me", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 170, "vibe": "Grammy winner Best Metal Performance · fastest Evil Empire · near-industrial grinding intensity", "dna": "Won Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance 1997. Fastest Evil Empire track at 170 BPM. Almost industrial in grinding intensity. Vocals recorded in Melbourne, Australia. De la Rocha's most aggressive vocal performance on the album. More abstract than most RATM tracks — about pushing limits and exhaustion as metaphor.", "style_prompt": "Industrial-speed metal-rap, 170 BPM, near-industrial grinding energy, Morello aggressive high-BPM attack, Brad Wilk precise fast drumming, de la Rocha maximum aggression, Grammy Best Metal Performance winner, O'Brien tight production, under 3:30, relentlessly intense", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast grinding heavy rap-metal song about exhaustion and limits pushed to the breaking point — the accumulation of every demand and every voice until the explosive refusal to be worn down. Visceral and physical rather than programmatic. The verses describe accumulation of pressure. The chorus is the refusal to be tired. Under 3:30. Maximum aggression."}, {"title": "Down Rodeo", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 84, "vibe": "Class war · Rodeo Drive luxury enclave · seething fury at exclusion", "dna": "Brings the class war to Rodeo Drive — Beverly Hills luxury shopping district as symbol of exclusion. De la Rocha's verse delivery at its most snarling. About what happens when the excluded masses march on the places that exclude them. Slow, heavy, seething.", "style_prompt": "Slow seething heavy rap-metal, 84 BPM, snarling low guitar riff, Brad Wilk thunderous slow groove, de la Rocha most snarling delivery, class war with Beverly Hills luxury enclave as target, Evil Empire O'Brien production, under 5:30, luxury imagery contrasting street fury", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow seething rap-metal song about class war — bringing the rage of the excluded to the places of exclusion: the luxury district, the gated community, the private club. Contrast specific details of wealth with the fury of those kept outside. The chorus is about what happens when the gates come down. Snarling and specific. Under 5:30."}, {"title": "Without a Face", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 99, "vibe": "Undocumented immigration · dehumanization of migrants · unusual melodic Morello guitar", "dna": "About the dehumanization of undocumented immigrants crossing the US-Mexico border — reduced to 'illegals' and statistics rather than human beings. Features a notably melodic Morello guitar figure unusual for Evil Empire. De la Rocha's most emotionally tender vocal on the album.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo heavy rap-metal with unusual melodic Morello guitar, 99 BPM, emotional weight beneath heavy groove, de la Rocha undocumented-immigration dehumanization lyric, border crossing imagery, Evil Empire O'Brien production, humanity-restoration as lyric goal, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo rap-metal song about the dehumanization of people crossing borders in search of survival — reduced to faceless statistics. The verses describe specific images from the migrant experience. The chorus is a restoration of humanity — naming the face that has been erased. Furious at the system, tender toward the people. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Wind Below", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 88, "vibe": "Most atmospheric Evil Empire track · almost psychedelic · oblique imagistic lyric", "dna": "Most atmospheric and unusual Evil Empire track. More psychedelic and less overtly political. Features Morello's most experimental extended techniques on the album. The lyric is more oblique and imagistic — a rare moment of sonic departure in the RATM catalog.", "style_prompt": "Atmospheric heavy rap-metal, 88 BPM, Morello extended experimental techniques, Brad Wilk hypnotic pocket, de la Rocha oblique imagistic lyric, meditative intensity, most unusual Evil Empire track, O'Brien production, under 5 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a heavy atmospheric rap-metal song that is more oblique and imagistic than political — using natural imagery (wind, earth, fire) as metaphors for forces gathering for change. More psychedelic than programmatic. The verses describe a world in transformation from below. The chorus is the emergence of those forces. Under 5 minutes. RATM at their most poetic."}, {"title": "Roll Right", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "bpm": 92, "vibe": "Gang violence as systemic product · criminalization of poverty · LA roots", "dna": "Addresses gang violence as a product of systemic poverty and neglect rather than individual moral failure. De la Rocha draws on his LA upbringing. Sympathetic toward gang members — understanding their circumstances as manufactured by the system. Alternate 'clean' lyrics printed in the CD booklet.", "style_prompt": "Slow heavy rap-metal, 92 BPM, LA West Coast groove, de la Rocha sympathetic gang-life-as-systemic-product lyric, Brad Wilk heavy pocket, Morello controlled riff, Evil Empire O'Brien production, poverty-as-cause analysis, under 5 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow heavy rap-metal song examining gang violence as a product of systemic poverty and abandonment — not individual moral failure. The verses describe the conditions that manufacture gang culture: economic exclusion, absent institutions, no alternatives. The narrator is analytical rather than condemnatory — these are people the system made. The chorus is understanding rather than judgment. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Year of tha Boomerang", "album": "Evil Empire", "year": 1994, "bpm": 84, "vibe": "Higher Learning soundtrack original · Evil Empire closer · karma and systemic blowback", "dna": "Originally released on the Higher Learning film soundtrack in 1994 before closing Evil Empire. The boomerang metaphor: violence and exploitation exported by the US will inevitably return. One of de la Rocha's most prophetic lyrics. The production has particular closing-statement gravity.", "style_prompt": "Slow heavy closing rap-metal, 84 BPM, prophetic boomerang-karma lyric, Brad Wilk thick powerful groove, Morello heavy riff, de la Rocha declaration-of-inevitability delivery, Evil Empire album closer, originally 1994 Higher Learning soundtrack, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow heavy rap-metal song built on the boomerang concept — what a nation exports (violence, exploitation, resource extraction) will inevitably return home. The verses catalogue specific acts of export. The chorus is the declaration of inevitability: it's coming back. Not vengeful — prophetic and certain. Under 4 minutes. The closing statement of an album."}, {"title": "Testify", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 117, "vibe": "BOLA opener · two-party system as illusion · Michael Moore video · 2000 election urgency", "dna": "Opens The Battle of Los Angeles. Featured in a Michael Moore-directed video. Released during the 1999-2000 election cycle. Argues both US political parties serve the same corporate interests — the illusion of democratic choice. De la Rocha's most rhythmically aggressive BOLA delivery. O'Brien's tightest production.", "style_prompt": "Fast aggressive BOLA rap-metal, 117 BPM, RATM tightest production, de la Rocha most rhythmically aggressive, two-party-system-as-illusion lyric, Michael Moore video era, Brad Wilk precise fast pocket, Morello dynamic riff, BOLA opener energy, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast aggressive rap-metal song arguing both major political parties serve the same corporate interests — the choice between them is an illusion managing dissent without changing anything. The verses name specific examples of bipartisan corporate compliance. The chorus demands the audience testify — witness and acknowledge the truth. Election year urgency. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Guerrilla Radio", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 103, "vibe": "Wah pedal groove · Commerford bass intro · anti-corporate media · Grammy Best Hard Rock", "dna": "Morello's prominent wah pedal creates the funky-aggressive texture. Commerford's bass intro is one of the most recognizable in hard rock. Grammy winner Best Hard Rock Performance. Targets corporate media control. The chorus is a call for alternative broadcasting.", "style_prompt": "Bass-forward funk rap-metal, 103 BPM, prominent bass guitar intro and groove, wah-filtered guitar funky-aggressive texture, hip-hop verse delivery, Brad Wilk thunderous pocket, anti-corporate-media lyric, BOLA O'Brien production, Grammy Best Hard Rock winner, under 3:30, locked rhythmic pocket", "lyric_prompt": "Write a groove-forward rap-metal song about independent uncensored media cutting through corporate noise. The verses name what corporate media buries. The chorus is a call to broadcast truth regardless of who controls the dial. Urgent and righteous. Under 3:30. The bass drives everything."}, {"title": "Calm Like a Bomb", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 90, "vibe": "Longest BOLA track · slow fuse energy · controlled verses to total detonation", "dna": "BOLA's longest track at 4:58. Entirely controlled fury in first two thirds, then total detonation in the final third. De la Rocha's most controlled verse delivery. Morello's most inventive BOLA guitar textures. RATM's most relentlessly locked groove.", "style_prompt": "Controlled-pressure rap-metal, 90 BPM, most locked RATM groove, de la Rocha most controlled delivery — contained building fury, diverse Morello textures building pressure, total explosion in final third, BOLA O'Brien production, 4:30–5 minute runtime, calm-then-bomb arc", "lyric_prompt": "Write a rap-metal song structured like a slow-burning fuse — entirely controlled first two thirds, then total detonation in the final third. Calm precise verses cataloguing injustice. Terrifyingly composed delivery. Then the final section ignites — control breaks, bomb goes off, screaming begins. The title IS the arc: calm like a bomb. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Mic Check", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 100, "vibe": "Corporate censorship of art · mic check as voice-control metaphor · artistic freedom", "dna": "The mic check as metaphor for corporate censorship — checking whether voices are allowed to speak. Targets corporate control of music and artistic expression. A meta-commentary on RATM's position as a radical band on a major label. Mid-tempo with particularly aggressive Morello riff.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo aggressive BOLA rap-metal, 100 BPM, aggressive Morello riff, Brad Wilk driving mid-tempo pocket, de la Rocha corporate-censorship-of-art lyric, mic check as voice-control metaphor, O'Brien tight production, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo rap-metal song about corporate control of artistic expression — who controls the microphone controls the message. The verses describe how the system co-opts, silences, or markets rebellion into harmlessness. The chorus is a declaration of unfiltered voice. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Sleep Now in the Fire", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 96, "vibe": "NYSE closed during filming · Michael Moore video · global capitalism and Wall Street target", "dna": "During filming of Michael Moore's video, the band caused the New York Stock Exchange to close its doors. Moore: 'No matter what happens, don't stop playing.' Morello's jabbing rhythmic riff is almost industrial. Targets global capitalism and American empire. The sardonic chorus addresses the wealthy comfortable in their privilege.", "style_prompt": "Industrial-funk rap-metal, 96 BPM, jabbing rhythmic guitar — almost percussive, no sustain, Brad Wilk thunderous pocket, de la Rocha rapid-fire political delivery, sneering contemptuous chorus, BOLA tighter production, Wall Street and empire target, under 3:30, relentless and locked", "lyric_prompt": "Write a jabbing industrial rap-metal song targeting global financial power. Rapid-fire indictments with contemptuous precision. The chorus is sardonic: telling the powerful to sleep comfortable in the fire they built. They profit while the world burns and call it civilization. Under 3:30. Every line a specific accusation."}, {"title": "Born of a Broken Man", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 86, "vibe": "Mental illness and systemic failure · most emotionally vulnerable BOLA track · complex Wilk drumming", "dna": "Also known as Broken Man. About mental illness and the failure of social systems to support those experiencing it — the criminalization and neglect of mentally ill people. Brad Wilk's most technically complex BOLA drumming. De la Rocha's most unusually vulnerable delivery on the album.", "style_prompt": "Slow emotional BOLA rap-metal, 86 BPM, most emotionally vulnerable track, Brad Wilk complex drumming, de la Rocha unusually vulnerable delivery, mental illness and systemic failure lyric, O'Brien BOLA production, less overtly political more personally painful, under 5 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow heavy rap-metal song about mental illness and the failure of every social system to support people experiencing it — the criminalization, neglect, and abandonment. More vulnerable than typical RATM — bearing witness to specific suffering, not sloganeering. The verses describe what it feels like to be failed by every system. The chorus states the cost of that failure. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Ashes in the Fall", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 90, "vibe": "Autumn and fire imagery · systemic collapse and regeneration · contemplative BOLA track", "dna": "Uses autumn and fire imagery to discuss systemic collapse and the possibility of regeneration from the ashes. One of BOLA's more contemplative slower-burning tracks. Morello in a more textural mode. De la Rocha's lyric is more metaphorical — natural imagery describing political reality.", "style_prompt": "Slow contemplative BOLA rap-metal, 90 BPM, Morello textural atmospheric guitar, Brad Wilk measured heavy pocket, de la Rocha autumn-fire metaphorical lyric, systemic collapse and regeneration, more imagistic than direct political naming, O'Brien BOLA production, under 4:30", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow heavy rap-metal song using autumn and fire imagery to describe systemic collapse — the fall of old structures and possibility of new growth from the ashes. More metaphorical and imagistic than direct political naming. Verses describe what is burning. The chorus asks or declares what comes after. Under 4:30."}, {"title": "War Within a Breath", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 98, "vibe": "BOLA closer · final original RATM statement · breath as moment of revolutionary decision", "dna": "Closes The Battle of Los Angeles — RATM's final original album before de la Rocha's October 2000 departure. The breath as metaphor for the space between oppression and resistance — the war that happens in a single moment of decision. De la Rocha's most deliberate closing performance.", "style_prompt": "Heavy closing-statement BOLA rap-metal, 98 BPM, final original album weight, de la Rocha deliberate closing delivery, Brad Wilk heavy foundational groove, Morello purposeful riff, breath-as-revolution metaphor, O'Brien BOLA production, under 5 minutes, last original RATM statement before dissolution", "lyric_prompt": "Write a heavy rap-metal song about the moment of decision — the single breath between oppression and resistance, the space where revolution either happens or doesn't. Every moment is a choice: comply or resist. The verses describe the accumulated weight making that breath necessary. The chorus is the breath itself — the decision. Under 5 minutes. The closing statement of the entire original catalog."}, {"title": "Maria", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 83, "vibe": "Slowest BOLA track · Virgin Mary as political symbol · religious iconography critique", "dna": "Slowest BOLA track. Uses Maria — the Virgin Mary — to examine how religious iconography is used to pacify and control populations, particularly in Latin American political contexts. One of de la Rocha's most complex lyrical performances. Morello in an unusually minimal approach.", "style_prompt": "Slowest heaviest BOLA track, 83 BPM, minimalist Morello guitar, Brad Wilk grinding slow pocket, de la Rocha complex religious-iconography lyric, Virgin Mary as political control symbol, Latin American political context, O'Brien production, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow heavy rap-metal song examining how religious iconography has been used to pacify populations — specifically how suffering gets reframed as holy, endurance as virtue, uprising as sin. The verses analyse this specific mechanism of control. The chorus reclaims the symbol for liberation. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "New Millennium Homes", "album": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "bpm": 88, "vibe": "Housing inequality · first dot-com boom displacement · LA class geography", "dna": "Released during the first dot-com boom when housing prices were dramatically rising and displacing lower-income communities — a phenomenon that has only accelerated since. Specifically about LA class geography — the contrast between luxury development and homelessness.", "style_prompt": "Heavy mid-tempo BOLA rap-metal, 88 BPM, housing inequality and class displacement lyric, dot-com-era displacement context, LA-specific class geography, Brad Wilk heavy BOLA pocket, Morello aggressive riff, O'Brien production, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a heavy rap-metal song about housing inequality and the displacement of communities by luxury development — the gleaming construction site next to the tent city. The verses contrast specific images of luxury development with homelessness. The chorus is about who the new millennium homes are actually for. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Maggie's Farm", "album": "Renegades", "year": 2000, "bpm": 89, "vibe": "Bob Dylan cover (1965) · folk protest to metal · labor exploitation refusal", "dna": "Bob Dylan original (1965). RATM transform Dylan's folk protest about labor exploitation into heavy funk-metal. The folk acoustic guitar becomes Morello's heavy metal riff. One of the most successful genre translations on Renegades — the political content maps perfectly onto RATM's aesthetic.", "style_prompt": "RATM-ized folk-to-metal protest, 89 BPM, Dylan labor-exploitation original in heavy funk-metal, Morello electric riff replacing acoustic guitar, Brad Wilk heavy pocket, de la Rocha transforming Dylan cadence, Renegades Rick Rubin production, labor refusal anthem, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a heavy rap-metal song in the spirit of refusing to work under oppressive exploitative conditions. The narrator has worked for every institution — the boss, the government, the church, the family — and refuses each one. Each verse is a different authority demanding compliance. The chorus is the refusal. Translate folk protest tradition into metal fury. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Microphone Fiend", "album": "Renegades", "year": 2000, "bpm": 93, "vibe": "Eric B. and Rakim cover (1988) · pure MC skills showcase · most purely hip-hop catalog entry", "dna": "Eric B. and Rakim original (1988). The most purely hip-hop track in the RATM catalog — a showcase for de la Rocha's MC skills, covering one of the definitive 1988 hip-hop tracks. Morello in a more hip-hop-production-influenced mode. Shows the direct hip-hop lineage of RATM's entire approach.", "style_prompt": "Hip-hop-influenced rap-metal, 93 BPM, Eric B and Rakim original RATM-ized, de la Rocha pure MC tribute delivery, Morello hip-hop-influenced mode, Brad Wilk hip-hop-influenced groove, Renegades Rick Rubin production, MC skills showcase, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a rap-metal song primarily showcasing pure MC lyrical skill — complex internal rhyme schemes, sophisticated wordplay, intricate syllabic patterns. The content is about the power and craft of the microphone itself. This is the most hip-hop track in the catalog: it's about rapping and what rapping can do. Under 4 minutes. Lead with lyrical complexity over political message."}, {"title": "Renegades of Funk", "album": "Renegades", "year": 2000, "bpm": 89, "vibe": "Afrika Bambaataa cover (1983) · hip-hop founding text · lineage of musical resistance", "dna": "Afrika Bambaataa original (1983) — one of the founding texts of hip-hop culture. RATM cover it as a tribute to the lineage of Black American resistance through music. The electronic production of the original becomes Morello-driven rock.", "style_prompt": "Funk-rock cultural-heritage cover, 89 BPM, Bambaataa original into RATM rock, hip-hop founding-text energy, Morello funk-rock groove, Brad Wilk driving pocket, de la Rocha hip-hop lineage delivery, Renegades Rick Rubin production, cultural resistance heritage, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a funk-metal song tracing the lineage of musical resistance — from funk to hip-hop to punk to rap-metal — as a continuous tradition of speaking truth to power. The song celebrates renegades who used music as a weapon across generations. The verses name specific moments and figures in this lineage. The chorus: this tradition continues through us. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "Ghost of Tom Joad", "album": "Renegades", "year": 2000, "bpm": 77, "vibe": "Bruce Springsteen cover (1995) · Grapes of Wrath lineage · most celebrated RATM cover", "dna": "Bruce Springsteen original (1995). RATM's most celebrated cover — transforming Springsteen's sparse acoustic song into heavy metal. The Ghost of Tom Joad — from Steinbeck's Grapes of Wrath — becomes the metaphor for resistance that cannot be killed. Originally released as a single in 1997. De la Rocha's most passionate vocal performance on Renegades.", "style_prompt": "Slow heavy Grapes-of-Wrath heritage cover, 77 BPM, Springsteen sparse acoustic original into heavy RATM statement, de la Rocha passionate economic-justice delivery, Brad Wilk heavy slow pocket, Morello transforming acoustic into electric metal riff, Renegades Rick Rubin production, most emotionally devastating cover, under 4:30", "lyric_prompt": "Write a slow heavy rap-metal song in the spirit of Tom Joad — about the ghost of resistance that cannot be killed because it lives in every act of solidarity. The verses describe specific faces of contemporary poverty that echo the 1930s Dust Bowl. The chorus is Tom Joad's promise: wherever there's a fight, I'll be there. Under 4:30. Most emotionally devastating track in the catalog."}, {"title": "How I Could Just Kill a Man", "album": "Renegades", "year": 2000, "bpm": 90, "vibe": "Cypress Hill cover (1991) · hip-hop swagger to metal fury · dual-register de la Rocha", "dna": "Cypress Hill original (1991). RATM transform the hip-hop classic into heavy metal. De la Rocha adopts hip-hop swagger verses before shifting to metal delivery — a rare dual-register performance. Shows the hip-hop-to-metal bridge at its most explicit.", "style_prompt": "Hip-hop-to-metal bridge cover, 90 BPM, Cypress Hill original transformed, de la Rocha hip-hop swagger verses to metal fury chorus, Morello metal riff replacing hip-hop beat, Brad Wilk metal groove, Renegades Rick Rubin production, dual-register vocal, under 3:30", "lyric_prompt": "Write a rap-metal song bridging hip-hop swagger and metal fury — the same narrator in two registers: controlled street-smart verses and explosive furious chorus. About the dangerous knowledge of what systemic violence breeds. Cool calculated verses erupting into explosion. Under 3:30. Most explicit hip-hop-to-metal bridge in the catalog."}, {"title": "Street Fighting Man", "album": "Renegades", "year": 2000, "bpm": 107, "vibe": "Rolling Stones cover (1968) · 1968 protest season · ambivalence transformed into declaration", "dna": "Rolling Stones original (1968), written during the worldwide 1968 protest movement. The original's ambivalence ('what can a poor boy do?') becomes in RATM's version a declaration rather than a question. They answer what Jagger left ambiguous.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo 1968-protest-spirit cover, 107 BPM, Stones original into RATM declaration, de la Rocha replacing Jagger ambivalence with certainty, Morello electric riff, Brad Wilk driving pocket, Renegades Rick Rubin production, under 3:30", "lyric_prompt": "Write a mid-tempo rap-metal song that answers the question 'what can a poor boy do' — with RATM's certainty rather than Jagger's ambivalence. The street fighter has plenty of options. The verses describe the world that makes street fighting necessary. The chorus is the answer: fight. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "Kick Out the Jams", "album": "Renegades", "year": 2000, "bpm": 137, "vibe": "MC5 cover (1969) · proto-punk anarchist energy · fastest Renegades track", "dna": "MC5 original (1969). The most purely punk track on Renegades — fastest at 137 BPM. MC5's anarchist Detroit politics directly influenced hardcore punk and RATM. The exhortation to free yourself maps perfectly onto RATM's aesthetic.", "style_prompt": "Fast proto-punk anarchist cover, 137 BPM, MC5 original transformed, fastest Renegades track, de la Rocha pure punk energy, Morello aggressive fast riff, Brad Wilk driving fast pocket, Renegades Rick Rubin production, anarchist liberation energy, under 3 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast anarchist punk-metal song about stripping away everything constraining authentic existence — kicking out the jams. The verses describe the constraints: conformity, authority, social expectation, corporate control. The chorus is the exhortation to remove them all and be free. Under 3 minutes. Maximum energy, maximum liberation."}, {"title": "Beautiful World", "album": "Renegades", "year": 2000, "bpm": 135, "vibe": "Devo cover (1981) · satirical consumer optimism · Morello new-wave guitar textures", "dna": "Devo original (1981). One of the most unexpected Renegades covers — new-wave satire about the beautiful world available only to the privileged. RATM transform the ironic new-wave original into heavy metal fury. Morello's guitar has unusual new-wave textures for the album.", "style_prompt": "Heavy new-wave-meets-metal satirical cover, 135 BPM, Morello unusual new-wave textures in heavy metal context, de la Rocha satirical-consumer-optimism lyric, Brad Wilk heavy pocket, Renegades Rick Rubin production, beautiful-world-only-for-the-privileged irony, under 4 minutes", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast heavy metal song with heavy satirical irony about the 'beautiful world' available to those with money — clean suburbs, safe neighborhoods, the beautiful life — as seen from outside it. The verses describe that beautiful world admiringly in a way that reveals its exclusivity. The chorus exposes who it's for and who it isn't. Under 4 minutes. Most satirically ironic track in the catalog."}], "albums": [{"title": "Rage Against the Machine", "year": 1992, "style_prompt": "Raw debut rap-metal, no click track natural tempo drift, GGGarth Richardson Sound City production, no samples keyboards or synthesizers — all live instruments, 75–163 BPM range most tracks 85–100 BPM, Morello experimental techniques without pedals, Brad Wilk loose powerful drumming, de la Rocha controlled-to-screaming vocal, political awakening and systemic critique, debut rawness and discovery energy", "lyric_prompt": "Write a debut-era RATM song embodying the political awakening of 1992 — raw, certain, naming specific enemies and systems. Emotional world: a young person discovering the reality of power, racism, exploitation, and media control for the first time and being seized by righteous fury. A manifesto — the opening statement of a band with something urgent to say. Controlled hip-hop verses erupting into metal fury. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Evil Empire", "year": 1996, "style_prompt": "Polished aggressive rap-metal, Brendan O'Brien production — tighter and more aggressive than debut, 83–170 BPM most tracks 84–107 BPM, Cole Rehearsal Studios Hollywood, Grammy-winning metal energy, heavier guitar distortion than debut, Brad Wilk more precise, de la Rocha more rhythmically complex, political maturity targeting specific institutions and ideologies, #1 Billboard 200", "lyric_prompt": "Write an Evil Empire-era RATM song — more polished and specific than the debut, with wider lyrical range from global capitalism to media manipulation to housing and immigration. Emotional world: four years into the fight, still furious but now precise in identifying mechanisms of power. The song should feel like a prosecutor's brief — specific, documented, unanswerable. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "The Battle of Los Angeles", "year": 1999, "style_prompt": "RATM peak production — O'Brien's tightest work, 83–172 BPM most tracks 88–100 BPM, most sonically diverse RATM album, Michael Moore collaboration era, de la Rocha most complex lyrical performances, Morello most inventive guitar work, Brad Wilk most technically precise, 2000 election year political urgency, final original-material statement", "lyric_prompt": "Write a BOLA-era RATM song — the final statement of a band at peak, with election year urgency and the knowledge this may be their last album. Emotional world: maximum political clarity, maximum musical ambition, maximum rage. The song should feel like a reckoning — everything the band has been building toward, delivered with absolute precision. Under 5 minutes."}, {"title": "Renegades", "year": 2000, "style_prompt": "Rick Rubin-produced covers album, RATM reimagining hip-hop and rock classics, 77–137 BPM average 106 BPM, brickwalled mastering, de la Rocha covering artists from Dylan to MC5 to Cypress Hill to Rakim, Morello translating acoustic and electronic sources into heavy metal, posthumous band statement after dissolution, homage to musical lineage of resistance", "lyric_prompt": "Write a Renegades-era RATM song honoring the tradition of musical resistance — covering or channeling a classic song of rebellion from any genre (folk, hip-hop, proto-punk, soul) and transforming it through heavy metal fury. A bridge between eras: the past tradition speaking through the present band. Show the continuous lineage of those who used music to fight power. Under 4 minutes."}]}, {"id": "russell_dickerson", "name": "Russell Dickerson", "genres": ["Country-Pop", "Country", "Country-Soul", "Contemporary Country"], "era": "2015–present", "color": "#e8943a", "bio": "Tennessee-born singer-songwriter who built a career writing exclusively about love, family, and the simple life. Five Billboard Country Airplay number ones. Over 3 billion streams. Writes almost exclusively about his wife Kailey and their growing family. The defining voice of feel-good, positive country when the genre trends dark — chest-thumping devotion anthems alongside tender domestic snapshots.", "producer_notes": "Casey Brown — signature clean bright Nashville sheen; acoustic guitar, bouzouki, keyboards. Josh Kerr — wider sonic range, 80s rock crunch and modern beats. All albums on Triple Tigers Records. R&B rhythms woven throughout. Co-writes every song except two cuts on the fourth album.", "catalog_style_prompt": "Bright polished Nashville country-pop with consistent R&B rhythmic undercurrent. Acoustic guitar as the foundation, pedal steel for warmth and texture, clean electric guitar accents on the bigger moments. Male vocal that is earnest and full-hearted — never ironically detached. Production sits between clean radio country and organic warmth. Energy ranges from tender ballad to chest-thumping anthem but always emotionally open. Layered harmonies on every chorus. The world sounds like a sunny Saturday.", "catalog_lyric_prompt": "Songs written from inside a loving, committed relationship — a man who found the person who made everything make sense and has been writing about her ever since. Themes: total devotion, the joy of ordinary life with the right person, small specific moments that prove love better than grand gestures, secure contentment rather than longing or loss. Lyric voice is specific and sensory — replacing every generic romance line with a true-feeling detail. Emotional register is warm, grateful, occasionally awestruck. The occasional faith reference is organic and unpreachy. This is the happy side of country.", "songs": [{"title": "Every Little Thing", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "The small unremarkable details that prove love · debut radio breakthrough · multi-platinum", "dna": "Third chart-topper from the debut. Built on the principle that hyperspecific sensory details — the way she sleeps, the sound of a particular laugh — carry more emotional weight than grand romantic declarations. Casey Brown's bright Nashville sheen gives it radio lift without sacrificing warmth. The song that established Dickerson as a songwriter who earns his emotion rather than assuming it.", "style_prompt": "Bright uptempo country-pop, energetic driving groove, acoustic guitar forward with punchy drum hits, pedal steel accents underneath, clean Nashville production, earnest joyful male tenor, layered harmonies lifting the chorus, warm and organic, built for radio but emotionally genuine", "lyric_prompt": "A devotion song built entirely on small specific unremarkable details — not grand gestures but the particular habits and mannerisms of one person that the narrator has catalogued with delighted precision. Each line should be a sensory snapshot that could only be about this specific person. The chorus is a declaration that every little thing adds up to everything. Avoid all generic romance — every line earns its place with specificity."}, {"title": "Yours", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "Total joyful belonging · debut breakthrough · iconic first-dance song", "dna": "The debut single that spent 39 weeks climbing to number one. Written about his wife Kailey — a man who was directionless before she gave him purpose, an anchor, a home. The Knot named it the ideal first-dance song. What makes it work is the specificity of the before — he describes exactly what kind of lost he was — which makes the belonging feel earned rather than assumed. Casey Brown production, three-part harmony on the chorus.", "style_prompt": "Warm devotional country-pop, mid-to-uptempo heartfelt energy, acoustic guitar foundation with soaring electric accents, pedal steel throughout, sweeping chorus with full harmonies, polished Nashville production, tender and full-hearted male vocal, R&B vocal phrasing inside a country production, deeply romantic without sentimentality", "lyric_prompt": "A declaration of belonging from a man who was directionless until this person arrived and gave him a reason, an anchor, a sense of home. The verse establishes exactly what kind of lost he was — specific not generic. The chorus is pure uncomplicated joy: he is completely hers. The bridge is a moment of overwhelmed gratitude, almost speechless. This should work as a first-dance song and as an anthem. Every cliché replaced with a true-feeling specific image."}, {"title": "Blue Tacoma", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "A truck as the container of all the best memories · summer carefree energy", "dna": "Second number one from the debut. The truck functions as a symbol of freedom and possibility — the vehicle where the most important moments happened, where life felt most open. More playful and kinetic than Yours, showing the range of the debut. Casey Brown's signature brightness at its most infectious.", "style_prompt": "Carefree uptempo country-pop, bright acoustic and electric guitar interplay, clean punchy production, charming playful male vocal, summer energy throughout, pedal steel accents, singalong chorus, R&B rhythmic groove underneath the country instrumentation", "lyric_prompt": "A playful sun-soaked song where a specific truck becomes the central symbol of freedom and love — the physical space where all the best moments happened, where everything felt possible. The narrator catalogues memories tied to that truck and the person beside him in it. Tone is joyful and present-tense, not wistful. The chorus declares what the truck represents. One specific memorable detail per verse."}, {"title": "Billions", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "Love described at cosmic scale · deep cut lyrical showcase", "dna": "Album track exploring the inadequacy of ordinary numbers to describe love — only the incomprehensible scale of the universe comes close. A deeper cut showing the lyrical ambition beneath the bright radio surface. Casey Brown production.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo country-pop, acoustic forward with warm electric accents, earnest male vocal reaching for something vast, pedal steel warmth, chorus builds to an expansive scale-of-love declaration, warm and organic", "lyric_prompt": "A love song that reaches for the largest possible numbers and concepts because ordinary measurements aren't enough — stars, years, the incomprehensible vastness of the universe as the only adequate comparison. Builds from small intimate moments in the verses to a cosmic declaration in the chorus. Tone is earnest and slightly awestruck, never overwrought."}, {"title": "All Fall Down", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "Vulnerability of loving someone completely · the admission of helplessness", "dna": "Debut album track about the particular vulnerability of falling all the way in love — acknowledging that this kind of love makes you helpless in the best way. More introspective than the uptempo singles, showing emotional range.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo vulnerable country-pop, acoustic forward, tender honest male vocal, pedal steel warmth, harmonies building on the chorus, warm and intimate emotional scale", "lyric_prompt": "A vulnerability confession — the narrator acknowledging that loving this person makes them completely helpless in the best possible way. Not bravado, just honesty. The verses describe what falling completely feels like. The chorus is the admission without apology."}, {"title": "Float", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "Weightlessness of love · being lifted off the ground", "dna": "Album track using physical sensation — floating, weightlessness, freedom from gravity — as the central metaphor for how this person makes the narrator feel. One of the more lyrically imaginative debut tracks.", "style_prompt": "Warm mid-tempo country-pop, acoustic guitar lead, pedal steel, male vocal light and lifted in tone and delivery, layered harmonies, major key joy", "lyric_prompt": "A song using the sensation of floating — weightless, lifted, free from gravity — as the core metaphor for what love does. The verses describe the physical feeling of being lifted. The chorus declares what causes it. The production and vocal performance should feel as light and buoyant as the subject."}, {"title": "MGNO (My Girl's Night Out)", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "Secure love · being happy watching her be free · the opposite of jealousy", "dna": "MGNO stands for My Girl's Night Out. A man who is home while his partner is out with friends and feels only adoration watching her be free and happy — no jealousy, no insecurity, just genuine delight. Slightly self-aware about how besotted he is. A charming, secure energy.", "style_prompt": "Warm playful country-pop, bright acoustic guitar, pedal steel accents, punchy drum groove, charming secure male vocal, slightly self-aware humor, singalong-ready chorus, Nashville clean production", "lyric_prompt": "A playful warm song from a man whose partner is out with her friends — and rather than jealousy, he feels nothing but genuine happiness watching her be free. He's at home, probably on the couch, and completely content thinking about how much he loves watching her enjoy life. Include a verse imagining what she and her friends are doing, delivered warmly and with humor. The bridge is the moment she comes home."}, {"title": "Would You Love Me", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "Hypothetical love · marveling at the specificity of what they have", "dna": "Album track built on a series of hypotheticals — would you love me if things were different? A deeper question about the nature of this specific love. The narrator marvels that it is this version of himself and this version of her that found each other.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo reflective country-pop, acoustic guitar, pedal steel warmth, tender questioning male vocal, layered harmonies, warm major key, intimate and personal", "lyric_prompt": "A series of gentle hypothetical questions exploring the nature of a specific love — would you love me if things were different, if we had met under other circumstances? The narrator is not anxious, just marveling at the specificity of what they have. The chorus holds the question openly."}, {"title": "Low Key", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "Preferring each other to everything else · quiet domestic joy", "dna": "The specific pleasure of preferring to stay home with this person over anything the world offers — not antisocial but simply because being with her is better. Quietly euphoric in its contentment.", "style_prompt": "Laid-back intimate country-pop, understated production, acoustic guitar, warm content male vocal, low-key energy that matches the lyric, pedal steel, nothing-else-needed feeling", "lyric_prompt": "A laid-back song about preferring to stay home with one person over everything else the world offers — not because the narrator is antisocial but because this is simply better. The verses describe all the things they could be doing. The chorus is the low-key declaration of preference."}, {"title": "You Look Like a Love Song", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "She doesn't inspire love songs — she IS one · songwriter's meta-romantic perspective", "dna": "A meta-romantic conceit from a songwriter's perspective — the woman he loves has become indistinguishable from the songs she inspires. One of the debut's more creatively interesting lyrical approaches.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo meta-romantic country-pop, acoustic guitar, warm polished production, delighted playful male vocal, pedal steel, singalong hook", "lyric_prompt": "A meta-romantic song from a songwriter's perspective — she doesn't just inspire love songs, she is one. The narrator describes her in the language of music: she has verses, a hook, a bridge, a key that makes everything resolve. The chorus declares that she looks exactly like a love song to him."}, {"title": "Twentysomething", "album": "Yours", "year": 2017, "vibe": "Young love and the broke beautiful twenties · figuring it out together", "dna": "The specific experience of being in your twenties — broke, uncertain, but choosing each other through all of it. A warmly nostalgic portrait of early adult life that resonates with couples who built something from very little.", "style_prompt": "Upbeat nostalgic country-pop, acoustic forward, warm male vocal, slightly nostalgic tone, pedal steel, singalong chorus, optimistic major key", "lyric_prompt": "An upbeat song about being in your twenties and figuring out love and life simultaneously — broke, uncertain, not sure where you're going, but having each other and that being enough. Specific details: the small apartment, the secondhand furniture, the big dreams. The chorus is the joy of having chosen each other through all of it."}, {"title": "Never Get Old", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "Specific shared moments that stay fresh no matter how many times they repeat", "dna": "Album opener with immediate energy. About the moments that never lose their feeling — specific rituals and habits shared with someone you love that remain as electric as the first time. High energy from the first second.", "style_prompt": "Foot-stomping uptempo country-pop, bright acoustic and electric guitar drive, punchy snare, energetic warm male vocal, layered harmonies, singalong chorus, Nashville polished production", "lyric_prompt": "A high-energy song about specific shared moments that never get old no matter how many times they repeat — the same song, the same restaurant, the same Saturday morning ritual. Each verse names a specific repeating moment. The chorus declares they never get old. High energy from the first line."}, {"title": "Home Sweet", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "Home is a person not a place · humble beginnings · ain't got much but got all we need", "dna": "B major. The opening verse travels from a honeymoon in Malibu to struggling to pay rent — a realistic portrait of early marriage. The chorus: 'Home sweet, you and me / Ain't got much but we got all we need.' Core idea: home is wherever she is. Warm, domestic, celebrating the simple life together.", "style_prompt": "Warm domestic country-pop, bright acoustic guitar, pedal steel warmth, hand claps, tender content male vocal, home-is-a-person lyric, simple-life celebration energy, porch-swing Sunday atmosphere, layered harmonies", "lyric_prompt": "A warm domestic song built on the idea that home is a person, not a place. A man who has traveled, struggled financially, moved around — and through it all found that wherever she is, that's home. Contrast moments of not-quite-having-it-together with the feeling of total contentment when they're together. The chorus is a simple joyful declaration: ain't got much but got all we need."}, {"title": "All Yours, All Night", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "Soaring total devotion anthem · built to showcase upper vocal register", "dna": "Described as one of Dickerson's finest vocal performances on Southern Symphony — a soaring anthem built to show off his upper register. An all-yours devotion declaration at the most polished Casey Brown production level.", "style_prompt": "Soaring uptempo devotion country-pop, polished Nashville production, powerful male vocal built to show off the upper register, electric guitar soar, pedal steel, sweeping chorus with full harmonies, major key grandeur", "lyric_prompt": "A soaring devotion anthem declaring the narrator is completely, unreservedly theirs — tonight and every night. The lyric has the scale to match the vocal ambition: this is a large declaration, not a quiet one. The verses build the case with specifics. The chorus is the declaration at full volume. The bridge describes what having her means to the rest of his life."}, {"title": "Love You Like I Used To", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "Long marriage that refuses to fade · pushing back against the assumption that love cools", "dna": "Lead single and fourth number one. The central idea is the promise that in a long marriage, love doesn't have to fade — he still loves her the way he did at the beginning. A direct counter-narrative to cultural assumptions about long-term relationships. Became a country radio staple.", "style_prompt": "Warm mid-tempo devotion country-pop, polished Southern Symphony production, earnest romantic male vocal, acoustic guitar, pedal steel warmth, layered harmonies, radio-ready hook, warm major key", "lyric_prompt": "A long-marriage song that refuses the assumption that love inevitably fades. The narrator is making a specific deliberate promise: I still love you the way I did when everything was new. The verses describe current moments that feel as electric as early love. The chorus is the promise itself."}, {"title": "Forever for a Little While", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "The paradox of moments that feel eternal but are fleeting", "dna": "The deliberately contradictory title captures the quality of certain moments — they feel eternal in the present even though they don't last. More traditional country production lean than most Southern Symphony tracks.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo traditional-leaning country-pop, fiddle accents, acoustic guitar, nostalgic warm male vocal, pedal steel, organic production with traditional country lean", "lyric_prompt": "A song built on the paradox of 'forever for a little while' — love that feels eternal in the moment but is finite. The narrator finds beauty in the fact that certain moments felt like forever even knowing they didn't last. The chorus holds the paradox with warmth, not sadness."}, {"title": "It's About Time", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "Three-voice collaboration · things coming together at exactly the right moment", "dna": "Features Florida Georgia Line — described as contemporary pop/hip-hop fusion, the most genre-diverse Southern Symphony track. Three vocalists trading verses and chorus sections. A celebration of timing — things clicking into place at exactly the right moment.", "style_prompt": "Contemporary country-pop with hip-hop fusion, upbeat energetic groove, three-vocal collaboration energy, modern production with rhythmic hip-hop influence, uptempo celebration, singalong hook", "lyric_prompt": "An uptempo celebration of timing — things coming together at exactly the right moment, meeting the right person at the right time, life's pieces clicking into place. Three distinct voices could trade verses. Tone is celebratory with swagger. The chorus is a declaration: it's about time."}, {"title": "Honey", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "The word honey as a container for an entire relationship's history", "dna": "A song built around the endearment — exploring all the ways that one word between two people contains the entire history of their relationship. Warm mid-album track giving the record a breather.", "style_prompt": "Warm mid-tempo country-pop, acoustic guitar, soft drum groove, pedal steel, gentle and loving male vocal, intimate domestic warmth", "lyric_prompt": "A song built entirely around the word 'honey' as an endearment — all the different contexts and emotional registers in which that one word is used between two people who love each other: everyday, tender, desperate, joyful. The narrator describes how the same word contains entire worlds depending on how it's said."}, {"title": "Southern Symphony", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "Biographical journey from a small tobacco town to the life built now", "dna": "The album's title track and most reflective moment. Dickerson described it as 'a trip from all the way back to my childhood growing up in a little cornfield and tobacco town to life now with Kails and our little Remington.' The quiet biographical centerpiece.", "style_prompt": "Reflective mid-tempo country-pop, acoustic guitar forward, warm biographical male vocal, pedal steel, gentle drum groove, southern imagery, journey-from-childhood-to-now narrative", "lyric_prompt": "A biographical journey structured as a trip from a small cornfield and tobacco town childhood through the years to the present — a wife he loves, children who run to the door when he comes home. Tone is warm and grateful, not nostalgic for something lost but appreciative of what was and what became. The title metaphor: the whole of his life is a southern symphony."}, {"title": "Come to Jesus", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "Faith woven naturally into love and life · moment of clarity about what matters", "dna": "Devout Christian Dickerson weaves faith organically into a love-and-life song — 'come to Jesus' as both a spiritual concept and a moment of arriving at clarity. Cited as one of his strongest examples of a catchy radio hook with genuine meaning underneath.", "style_prompt": "Upbeat faith-meets-love country-pop, bright acoustic guitar, pedal steel warmth, earnest joyful male vocal, Christian faith organic and unpreachy, singalong hook, major key uplift", "lyric_prompt": "An upbeat song where 'come to Jesus' is the central concept — a moment of arriving at clarity and truth about what matters most in life. The narrator has had a come-to-Jesus moment about love, family, and faith, and the song describes what that moment of clarity revealed. Faith is present but organic, not a sermon."}, {"title": "Waiting for You", "album": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "vibe": "80s-tinged album closer · saxophone solo · the finest Southern Symphony track per critics", "dna": "Described by Entertainment Focus as the finest track on Southern Symphony. Features an unexpected saxophone solo. 80s-tinged production — the most sonically unusual Dickerson track, the synth and saxophone giving it a different character than anything else in the catalog. Album closer.", "style_prompt": "80s-tinged country-pop album closer, 80s pop synth touches, saxophone solo, acoustic guitar underneath, warm hopeful male vocal, retro shimmer production, album-closing emotional weight", "lyric_prompt": "An 80s-tinged song about the anticipation of waiting for someone — the specific quality of time spent holding space for them, knowing they're coming, making everything ready. The 80s production influence should be felt in the lyric rhythm: a slightly more cinematic dramatic quality. The saxophone break is a moment of pure feeling. A resolution that closes an album."}, {"title": "Blame It on Being Young", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Charming warm retrospective on youthful mistakes · self-aware not apologetic", "dna": "Album opener. About blaming youthful mistakes on simply being young — charming, self-aware, slightly amused. Sets the tone for an album that spans from teenage years to fatherhood.", "style_prompt": "Uptempo charming country-pop, wider sonic range than debut era, bright guitar drive, modern production with acoustic warmth, charming self-aware male vocal, singalong hook", "lyric_prompt": "A warm charming retrospective on youthful mistakes — blaming them on simply being young. Not apologetic, just self-aware and slightly amused. The verses catalogue specific youthful foolishness with affection. The chorus is the absolution. These mistakes made him who he is."}, {"title": "Sorry", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Genuine warm apology for small consistent relationship failures · honest not dramatic", "dna": "A genuine warm apology to his wife — not for dramatic failures but for the small consistent ways he falls short: being distracted, taking her for granted, putting other things first. Not groveling, not dramatic — just honest. One of the more emotionally mature tracks in the catalog.", "style_prompt": "Warm mid-tempo apology country-pop, acoustic guitar forward, pedal steel tenderness, sincere gentle male vocal, soft drum groove, clean Nashville production, intimate scale", "lyric_prompt": "A genuine warm apology song for the small consistent ways the narrator falls short — not dramatic failures but being distracted, taking her for granted, putting other things first. Not groveling, just honest. The chorus is a direct specific apology that names what he did wrong rather than a generic 'I'm sorry.' The bridge is his reminder of why she's worth becoming better for."}, {"title": "She Likes It", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Slinky soul-R&B fusion · two-voice duet · doing things because she likes them", "dna": "Multi-platinum lead single featuring Jake Scott — discovered online by Dickerson who invited him to a writing session. Described as 'slinky, soul-infused.' The most R&B-influenced Dickerson production. A song about doing specific things simply because she likes them — her happiness becomes his happiness.", "style_prompt": "Slinky soul-infused country-pop duet, R&B groove under country-pop, two male vocals blending, funky rhythmic feel, warm electric guitar, most R&B-forward Dickerson production", "lyric_prompt": "A slinky soul-infused song with two male vocalists about doing specific things because she likes them — her happiness is his happiness, and there's a specific joy in doing the things that make her light up. R&B swagger mixed with country warmth. The verses catalogue things done because she likes them. The chorus is the declaration."}, {"title": "I Still Believe", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Authentic Christian faith declaration · conviction through everything", "dna": "Faith anthem — a declaration of continued Christian belief, written by a devout believer rather than a commercial faith-radio calculation. Authentic conviction that has survived whatever the narrator has been through.", "style_prompt": "Faith declaration country-pop, acoustic guitar, pedal steel, earnest convicted male vocal, warm major key, layered harmonies, anthem-scale chorus", "lyric_prompt": "A personal faith declaration from a man who still believes — not despite everything but through everything. Authentic conviction, not a calculated pitch. The verses describe what has been survived and what has been doubted. The chorus declares that through it all, belief remains. Strong and grateful, not preachy."}, {"title": "Big Wheels", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Gravel road guarantee · rural identity pride · never getting beyond your raising", "dna": "About rural identity and the pride of staying true to where you came from even as success grows. A chest-thumping guarantee: he'll never get beyond his raising.", "style_prompt": "Uptempo rural-identity country-pop, gravel-road energy, electric guitar drive, pedal steel, proud grounded male vocal, chest-thumping energy, singalong hook", "lyric_prompt": "An uptempo song about rural identity and staying true to where you came from — the gravel road, the small town, the raised-right upbringing — no matter how far success takes you. The narrator makes a guarantee: never getting beyond his raising. Specific images of that upbringing in the verses. The chorus is the proud declaration."}, {"title": "I Remember", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Hyperspecific memory snapshots · falling in love encoded in permanent detail", "dna": "Described as capturing 'forever-young fun like a country-pop polaroid.' About the specific memories encoded from falling in love — the exact details of particular moments permanently stored.", "style_prompt": "Upbeat memory-snapshot country-pop, bright acoustic and electric guitar, vivid specific male vocal, layered harmonies, singalong chorus, major key warmth, polaroid energy", "lyric_prompt": "An upbeat song built on hyperspecific memory recall — the exact details of particular moments from falling in love: what song was playing, what she was wearing, what she said, how the light fell. These details have been encoded permanently. Each verse is one specific memory with that polaroid specificity. The chorus: I remember everything."}, {"title": "I Wonder", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "What-if of the road not taken · haunted by a near-miss alternate timeline", "dna": "About pondering what life would look like if he and his wife hadn't reconciled a breakup during dating. A rare Dickerson exploration of uncertainty and roads not taken — what would his life look like without that reconciliation? One of the catalog's most emotionally nuanced tracks.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo reflective country-pop, acoustic guitar, pedal steel, searching slightly haunted male vocal, layered harmonies building on chorus, warm major key with emotional undercurrent", "lyric_prompt": "A reflective song about being quietly haunted by the question of what life would look like if one specific moment had gone differently — specifically if a relationship had not been reconciled after a breakup. The narrator is grateful for the life he has but can't help wondering about the alternate timeline. Tender wondering, not regret. The chorus holds the question."}, {"title": "God Gave Me a Girl", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Becoming a father · awestruck immediate permanent love · watching his wife as a mother", "dna": "Fifth number one. Inspired by the birth of his child and watching his wife Kailey sing to her. Different in emotional register from his wife songs — this is bigger, more reverent, the feeling of being completely undone by a person you just met.", "style_prompt": "Uplifting high-energy fatherhood country-pop, bright electric and acoustic guitar blend, big drum production, powerful reverent male vocal, soaring chorus with wide harmonies, bright open major key", "lyric_prompt": "A reverent awestruck fatherhood song from a man who didn't fully understand what he was capable of feeling until the moment his child arrived. The chorus is a declaration of fatherly devotion using the 'God gave me' concept — she is a gift he didn't earn. Include a verse about watching her sleep, or her small hands, or her laugh. The bridge is watching her mother with her and being undone by both of them."}, {"title": "All the Same Friends", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "The shared social world of a long relationship · community built together", "dna": "About the specific phenomenon of a long relationship where your social world has become completely intertwined — her friends are your friends, your friends are her friends, separating you would be impossible.", "style_prompt": "Uptempo community-of-love country-pop, electric and acoustic guitar drive, warm inclusive male vocal, pedal steel accents, singalong chorus, major key warmth", "lyric_prompt": "An uptempo song about the shared social world of a long relationship — the friends who are now your friends because of her, the community built together, the people who know both of you so completely that separation would be impossible. The chorus celebrates all the same friends."}, {"title": "Beers to the Summer", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Toast to the season · specific summer joy · outdoor festival energy", "dna": "A toast to summer — the specific freedom and warmth of that season and everything it represents. An acoustic version was included on the deluxe edition.", "style_prompt": "Uptempo summer celebration country-pop, bright guitar energy, outdoor festival feel, carefree joyful male vocal, hand claps, singalong chorus, sunshine major key, arms-in-the-air energy", "lyric_prompt": "An uptempo toast to summer — cataloguing the specific freedom and warmth of the season: the late nights, the lake days, the windows-down drives. The narrator catalogues specific summer details that feel universally relatable. The chorus is the raised glass."}, {"title": "She's Why", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "The specific why behind everything · playful side of a mature relationship", "dna": "About all the specific ways she is the reason behind everything — why he does things, why he is who he is. Described as capturing 'the playful side of a mature relationship.'", "style_prompt": "Playful mid-tempo relationship country-pop, acoustic guitar, pedal steel, warm slightly teasing male vocal, layered harmonies, playful but genuine, major key warmth", "lyric_prompt": "A playful song about all the specific ways she is the reason behind everything — she's why he bothers, why he tries, why he comes home, why he can't stop smiling at nothing. Warm and slightly teasing — the playful side of a long secure relationship. The chorus is the declaration of why."}, {"title": "18", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "80s-pop production · wishing you could go back to the moment you met", "dna": "Described as tapping into 'pulsating 80s pop, using the throwback energy to imagine going back in romantic time.' About wishing you could go back to being 18 and meeting her again — not because anything is wrong, but because the beginning was so good you want to relive it.", "style_prompt": "80s-influenced country-pop, synth shimmer under acoustic guitar, reverb-drenched 80s pop atmosphere, nostalgic romantic male vocal, pulsating 80s energy in country framework, layered harmonies", "lyric_prompt": "An 80s-influenced song about the romantic wish to go back to being younger and meet her again — not because anything is wrong now but because the beginning was so electric, so charged with possibility, that the narrator wants to live it again. The chorus is the wish: take me back."}, {"title": "Over and Over", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Choosing her every day · the active daily renewal of love", "dna": "About the active daily choice that long love requires — choosing her over and over, not passive but deliberate. An acoustic version was included on the deluxe edition.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo tender devotion country-pop, acoustic guitar warmth, pedal steel, earnest deliberate male vocal, layered harmonies building chorus, major key warmth, intimate emotional register", "lyric_prompt": "A tender song about the active daily choice to love someone — the recognition that love is not passive but something you choose over and over, every day. The narrator is making this choice consciously and with full gratitude. The verses describe specific moments of making that choice. The chorus: I'd choose you over and over."}, {"title": "Drink to This", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Toast to ordinary life moments · the specific things worth raising a glass to", "dna": "A toast to the good life — not a generic party song but a specific celebration of ordinary moments worth raising a glass to. An acoustic version on the deluxe edition.", "style_prompt": "Uptempo celebration country-pop, bright guitar drive, warm celebratory male vocal, specific ordinary-moments lyric, pedal steel, singalong chorus, major key joy", "lyric_prompt": "An uptempo toast song — a specific celebration of ordinary moments that make life worth raising a glass to: the Tuesday nights, the front porch conversations, the small victories. The narrator catalogues specific moments that deserve a toast. The chorus is the raising of the glass."}, {"title": "Just Like Your Mama", "album": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "vibe": "Letter to his son · hopes he'll be like his mother · album closer · child cameo", "dna": "Co-written with Grammy-winning songwriter Lori McKenna. Dedicated to Dickerson's son Remington — the album closes with a special appearance by the toddler. Described as 'incredibly moving.' The lyric: 'Just like your mama / No bull and no drama / You'll know who you are / And you'll know who you aint.' The most emotionally resonant album closer in the catalog.", "style_prompt": "Sparse emotionally moving country-pop album closer, sparse acoustic arrangement, tender male vocal addressed to a child, pedal steel warmth, Lori McKenna lyrical precision influence, a toddler's voice heard briefly", "lyric_prompt": "A sparse emotionally moving song addressed from a father to his young son — a letter about who the narrator hopes his son will become. Specifically: that he will be like his mother — no bull, no drama, knowing who he is and who he isn't, keeping his golden heart on his sleeve, not letting the world take his shine. The final verse is addressed to both son and mother simultaneously: you're better than my wildest dreams, just like your mama. A toddler's voice can be heard briefly."}, {"title": "Dust", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "A nod to Dust on the Bottle · fleeting romance that lingers in memory", "dna": "Album opener. A wistful narrative about a fleeting romance that lingers like dust — nodding to David Lee Murphy's iconic 'Dust on the Bottle.' Apple Music noted Dickerson's 'smooth croon on a wistful narrative about lost romance.' One of his most emotionally complex openers.", "style_prompt": "Wistful opening country-pop, warm acoustic guitar, pedal steel, smooth aching male vocal, fleeting-romance-memory lyric, Famous Back Home country-soul warmth with modern sheen, opening tone-setter", "lyric_prompt": "A wistful song about a fleeting romance that lingers in memory — not a long relationship but a brief connection that left a coating you can't quite shake. The central image is dust: the way certain memories coat everything, light but persistent. The tone is more complex than typical — there is ache here, not just warmth. Nod to classic 90s country imagery."}, {"title": "Sippin' on Top of the World", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Full-throttle weekend anthem · stadium-ready joy · the simple life at its best", "dna": "First outside cut of Dickerson's career. Described as a 'full-throttle weekend anthem bursting with joy and freedom' with 'cans-up energy.' Stadium-ready. Windows-down road-trip energy.", "style_prompt": "Full-throttle stadium-ready country-pop anthem, uptempo driving energy, Famous Back Home country-soul with modern muscle, euphoric free male vocal, electric guitar drive, pedal steel, biggest chorus of the album, arms-in-the-air energy", "lyric_prompt": "A full-throttle weekend anthem about the specific joy of the best days: the road trip, the lake, the friends, the ice-cold drink, feeling on top of the world for no more reason than the sun is out and life is good. The verses catalogue the specific elements of this day. The chorus is the declaration of being on top of the world. Stadium singalong energy."}, {"title": "Happen to Me", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Disbelieving gratitude · how did I get this lucky · danceable arena energy", "dna": "Fifth number one. Biggest streaming debut of Dickerson's career. Features palm-muted guitars and spontaneous rocker energy. Co-written with the writer of Cyndi Lauper's 'Girls Just Want to Have Fun.' His most danceable, arena-ready hit.", "style_prompt": "Uptempo arena country-pop, palm-muted electric guitar driving rhythm, punchy snare, danceable modern country-pop-rock, energetic charismatic male vocal, 80s pop-rock influence, singalong anthemic chorus, spontaneous rocker energy", "lyric_prompt": "A fast danceable country-pop anthem from a man who is genuinely amazed that the most incredible woman he's ever encountered chose him. Joyful disbelieving gratitude — how did I get this lucky? The chorus is a big singalong explosion about how she happened to him — like a force of nature he didn't see coming. 80s pop-rock energy: palm-muted guitars, spontaneous rocker feel."}, {"title": "Worth Your Wild", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Funky 80s country-pop · Lionel Richie influence · being worth the chase", "dna": "Third single. Described as 'funky, Lionel Richie-style 80s pop-country.' The most funk-influenced Dickerson production — about being worth someone's wildness, worth the chase, worth going wild for.", "style_prompt": "Funky 80s pop-country, Lionel Richie-influenced funk groove under country production, charming swaggering male vocal, danceable energy, 80s funk guitar, singalong hook, most funk-forward Dickerson track", "lyric_prompt": "A funky 80s-influenced country-pop song about being worth someone's wildness — worth the chase, worth the risk, worth throwing caution to the wind for. The narrator makes the case with Lionel Richie funk-pop swagger. The chorus is the declaration of worth."}, {"title": "Heard It in a Country Song", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Love letter to country music · 90s Easter eggs · barbecue stains and grape snow cones", "dna": "A love letter to country music laced with lyrical Easter eggs referencing 90s country song imagery — barbecue stains, grape snow cones, the watermelon crawl. '90s-inspired hooks with Dickerson's roots-R&B groove.'", "style_prompt": "90s-tribute country-pop with R&B groove, 90s country production shimmer, warm nostalgic male vocal, lyrical Easter eggs from 90s country imagery, swagger-filled throwback with modern polish", "lyric_prompt": "A swagger-filled love letter to country music itself — packed with Easter-egg references to classic 90s country imagery: the barbecue stains, the snow cones, the tailgates, the specific sensory details that define the genre. The narrator heard all of life's important moments in a country song first. The chorus: I heard it in a country song. 90s shimmer under modern R&B groove."}, {"title": "Sunrise in My Silverado", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Golden-hour truck magic · the perfect suspended moment", "dna": "Described as shimmering 'like a magic-hour anthem with a box-wine buzz.' An 80s pop shimmer with golden-hour country charm.", "style_prompt": "Golden-hour uptempo country-pop, 80s pop shimmer, magic-hour energy, warm golden male vocal, electric guitar shimmer, pedal steel, Famous Back Home production, singalong hook", "lyric_prompt": "A golden-hour song about a perfect sunrise or sunset seen from a truck — the specific feeling of that magic-hour light, the carefree warmth of the moment, the person beside you, everything suspended and perfect. The narrator describes one of those specific moments where time feels different. The chorus celebrates that feeling."}, {"title": "For a Truck", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Derailed plans leading to romantic destiny · a truck as the unlikely catalyst", "dna": "Described as 'a tale of derailed plans and romantic destiny.' A story song about how a truck-related circumstance derailed original plans but led to meeting someone — the truck as the unexpected catalyst of everything.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo story-song country-pop, acoustic guitar forward, pedal steel warmth, warm narrative male vocal, derailed-plans-lead-to-destiny lyric, storytelling verse structure building to chorus declaration", "lyric_prompt": "A country-pop story song about derailed plans that led to romantic destiny — how a truck (breaking down, being borrowed, being in the wrong place at the right time) became the unlikely catalyst for meeting the person who changed everything. The verses tell the story with specific narrative detail. The chorus is the realization that what seemed like bad luck was actually destiny."}, {"title": "Love That I Love You", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Meta-awareness of loving her · soul-mate memories with rhythmic roots", "dna": "Described as pairing 'soul-mate memories with a surge of rhythmic roots.' About the meta-awareness of loving this particular person — the specific love of loving them.", "style_prompt": "R&B-influenced country-pop, rhythmic roots groove, warm R&B-inflected male vocal, soul-mate-memories lyric, electric guitar with soul texture, pedal steel, singalong hook", "lyric_prompt": "An R&B-grooved country-pop song about the meta-awareness of loving this specific person — the love of loving them. Soul-mate memories with rhythmic swagger. The verses describe specific memories that confirm this is it. The chorus: I love that I love you."}, {"title": "Never Leave", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Stripped-down plea · Vince Gill feature · outside cut · demo-style intimacy", "dna": "Second outside cut of Dickerson's career. Features Vince Gill — a country legend lending his voice to a stripped-down plea for redemption. Demo-style intimate production, the most sparse and raw track in the entire catalog.", "style_prompt": "Stripped-down intimate country-pop plea, sparse demo-style production, acoustic guitar only or near-only, most vulnerable pleading male vocal in the catalog, country legend harmony vocal, raw and unguarded", "lyric_prompt": "A stripped-down sparse country-pop plea to someone not to leave — to give one more chance, to allow the narrator to become the person who deserves them. The most vulnerable and unguarded track in the catalog: no production armor, no uptempo energy, just one man asking one person not to go. A country legend harmonizes on the chorus."}, {"title": "Bones", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Love at the structural level · unconditional and lasting · pre-album single", "dna": "Pre-album single about lasting unconditional love — the kind that goes all the way down to the bones, that is structural to who you are.", "style_prompt": "Mid-tempo lasting-love country-pop, acoustic guitar and warm electric, pedal steel, tender certain male vocal, layered harmonies building chorus, Famous Back Home country-soul warmth, major key depth", "lyric_prompt": "A mid-tempo song about love that goes down to the bones — structural, physical, part of how the narrator is built. The verses describe what that kind of love looks like in practice. The chorus is the declaration of its depth: it's in my bones."}, {"title": "16 and Me", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Letter to his teenage self · small-town dreams reframed · famous at home", "dna": "Reflects the Famous Back Home album's central theme applied autobiographically. Dickerson: 'Growing up in a small town, I had this idea I'm going to make it out of here... But then you have a family and it's like, Actually, all I want to do is be famous at home.'", "style_prompt": "Warm nostalgic country-pop with modern polish, acoustic guitar with subtle synth bed, 80s-influenced touches, warm sincere reflective male vocal, small-town growing-up imagery, bittersweet-hopeful nostalgic tone", "lyric_prompt": "A warm nostalgic song structured as a letter to a teenage self. The narrator speaks from genuine specific contentment: a wife he loves completely, kids who run to the door when he gets home. He tells his younger self what's coming — not to prepare him but to reassure him. He thought famous meant big stages — turns out it means being famous at home. Specific small-town teenage details in the verses. The chorus is a warm address to that younger self."}, {"title": "Famous Back Home", "album": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "vibe": "Album title and closer · the only fame that matters · family-first realization", "dna": "Album title track and emotional high point. Described as celebrating 'the home life he's built with his family over the trappings of fame and commercial success.' The biggest stage he ever wanted was always just his front door.", "style_prompt": "Reflective album-closing country-pop ballad, acoustic guitar forward, warm pedal steel, emotional full-circle male vocal, layered harmonies building to emotional chorus, tender balladry, Famous Back Home emotional resolution", "lyric_prompt": "A reflective closing ballad about the realization that the only fame that matters is being famous at home — with kids who run to the door, a wife who knows you completely. The narrator has built a career, played big stages — and the thing that moves him most is coming home and his kids come running. The journey comes full circle. The chorus declares what famous really means to him. The most emotionally resonant song in the catalog."}], "albums": [{"title": "Yours", "year": 2017, "style_prompt": "Bright warm country-pop debut — the sound of a clear Nashville morning. Acoustic guitar as the spine, pedal steel as the warmth, clean electric guitar lifting the big moments. Casey Brown's polished bright sheen throughout. Male vocal that is earnest, full-hearted, and completely unironic about love. R&B rhythmic undercurrent under every track. Energy is upbeat and emotionally open.", "lyric_prompt": "Songs written from inside a new marriage to the person who changed everything. The emotional world: a man who was directionless and lost before she arrived, now completely oriented around her and grateful for it. Hyperspecific sensory details rather than generic romance — every line earns its place by being true-feeling and particular. Themes: total devotion, belonging, the specific joy of having found your person."}, {"title": "Southern Symphony", "year": 2020, "style_prompt": "More confident and polished than the debut — Casey Brown's production at its peak. Wider energy range: from foot-stomping to tender to an unexpected saxophone-and-synth closer. R&B groove influence more prominent. A collaboration track brings in a hip-hop-inflected contemporary production. Still grounded in acoustic guitar and pedal steel but willing to surprise.", "lyric_prompt": "A more mature and self-assured record. Still deeply romantic but now also encompassing the biographical journey — the small town childhood, the marriage that has grown and deepened, the beginnings of fatherhood. Faith woven in organically. The emotional world of a man who has built the life he dreamed of and is making specific sense of it."}, {"title": "Russell Dickerson", "year": 2022, "style_prompt": "The widest sonic range of the catalog. Josh Kerr co-production brings 80s pop influences, more electric guitar drive, and an explicit funk-soul crossover. The most R&B-influenced Dickerson record — the She Likes It duet signals the direction. 15 tracks spanning from teenage years to fatherhood. Still anchored in acoustic warmth but willing to push into 80s nostalgia, soul, and modern country-rock.", "lyric_prompt": "The broadest creative range: from charming retrospective on youth to fatherhood revelation to a rare moment of honest self-doubt. Dickerson: 'It's from when I was 16 to when I became a dad — that's Russell Dickerson.' Themes cover ground not previously explored: genuine apology, religious faith as a separate track, rural identity pride, and the overwhelming love of becoming a parent."}, {"title": "Famous Back Home", "year": 2025, "style_prompt": "The most adventurous production of the catalog. Josh Kerr and Casey Brown co-producing. Country-soul foundation with 80s rock crunch, palm-muted guitar drive, Lionel Richie funk influence, and stadium-scale anthems. Two outside cuts for the first time. A Vince Gill collaboration at the sparse intimate end, a danceable arena anthem at the other. Wider sonic palette than any previous record.", "lyric_prompt": "A record built around one central realization: being famous back home — famous with his kids, famous with his wife — is the only fame that matters. Themes: the best-days lifestyle celebration, nostalgic letters to younger selves, golden-hour moments, the humble domestic life valued over public success. Also the most stylistically diverse lyrics in the catalog: wistful fleeting romance, broad summer anthems, and a raw stripped-down plea."}]}, {"id": "taylor_male", "name": "Taylor Swift / Antonoff (Male Era)", "genres": ["Synth-Pop", "Indie Pop", "Pop", "Folk-Pop", "Dream-Pop"], "era": "2014–2022", "color": "#9b6dff", "bio": "Male-perspective reframe of 14 Jack Antonoff-produced Taylor Swift songs, plus per-album prompts for 1989, Reputation, Lover, folklore, evermore, and Midnights. The Antonoff signature: Juno-6 synth arpeggios, reverb-drenched vocals placed high in the mix, pitched-up detuned elements, 80s-influenced drum machines, emotional vulnerability over polished production.", "producer_notes": "Jack Antonoff — Juno-6 synth, analog warmth, Brooklyn home-studio feel. No artist names in Suno prompts — use genre/era descriptors only.", "songs": [{"title": "Welcome to New York", "album": "1989", "year": 2014, "bpm": 117, "vibe": "Euphoric city rebirth anthem", "dna": "Juno-106 synth arpeggios, insistent disco drum machine, no guitar — pure synth-pop. Broad, cinematic, manifesto-like. Male version: arriving in a new city, shedding old identity.", "style_prompt": "Euphoric 80s synth-pop, Juno synth arpeggio opening, insistent disco drum machine, no guitar, layered choral male vocals high in the mix, processed vocal harmonies, cinematic city-anthem energy, pure electronic production, bright and wide stereo field, 117 BPM, triumphant rebirth tone, warm analog synth bass, New Wave-influenced, emotionally open and celebratory", "lyric_prompt": "Write an anthem for a man who has just moved to a new city and is shedding his entire old identity — old name, old reputation, old heartbreaks. The tone is euphoric and almost manifesto-like, not reflective. The city itself becomes a character: it doesn't know his past, it offers him a blank slate. The chorus should be a huge repeated hook using the city (or a metaphor for it) as the central image. Structure: short punchy verses building momentum → massive anthem chorus with layered imagery → second verse with a single new detail → same chorus → brief bridge about what he's leaving behind → final exploding chorus. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "Out of the Woods", "album": "1989", "year": 2014, "bpm": 92, "vibe": "Anxious love · relentless percussion · are we safe yet?", "dna": "Gibson ES-330, Juno-6, Vox AC30, Fine Young Cannibals-inspired snare. Half-time feel on chorus. Relentlessly driving percussion. Chorus keeps asking the same question — creates anxiety through repetition.", "style_prompt": "Anxious 80s synth-pop, hollow-body guitar texture, Juno synth swells, vintage Vox amp warmth, relentless driving drum pattern with half-time chorus feel, sampled snare snap, building tension throughout, male tenor vocal urgent and breathless, repeated questioning hook chorus, no dynamic rest — constant forward momentum, wide reverb field, 92 BPM with relentless pulse, emotionally unstable love song energy", "lyric_prompt": "Write a song from the perspective of a man in a relationship that has always felt one step from disaster — a love that was passionate but built on anxiety and near-misses. The central chorus question should be a repeated urgent refrain asking whether they've finally made it through. The verses recall specific moments of danger or instability. The bridge should be the moment where he realizes the relationship is over and declares some kind of freedom or resignation. The emotional tone is exhausted hope. Percussion and urgency should be felt in the lyric rhythm. Under 3:45."}, {"title": "I Wish You Would", "album": "1989", "year": 2014, "bpm": 170, "vibe": "Fast-tempo longing · 2am wishes", "dna": "Started as an Antonoff guitar instrumental, 170 BPM. Driving rhythm guitar, Juno synths. The chorus is a list of desperate wishes. Simple, declarative, longing.", "style_prompt": "Fast-tempo 80s synth-pop, 170 BPM, driving rhythm guitar energy, Juno synth accents, punchy tight drum machine, male vocal urgent and raw, late-night restless energy, no vocal layering on verses — intimate and direct, layered harmonies exploding on chorus, simple declarative chorus lyrics built on repeated wish/longing structure, bright guitar-forward production with synth bed, emotionally desperate but melodically upbeat", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast-tempo pop song from a man's perspective — he's alone at 2am, driving past her street, unable to stop thinking about his ex and wishing she'd come back. The chorus is built entirely around a repeated 'I wish you would...' structure — a list of desperate, specific wishes. The verses are short and urgent — setting the late-night scene, his restlessness. The bridge should be the moment he almost calls her and stops himself. Under 3:15."}, {"title": "You Are in Love", "album": "1989", "year": 2014, "bpm": 72, "vibe": "Third-person quiet love observation", "dna": "Antonoff's warmest, most intimate production — frequencies cut above a certain range for warmth. Spacious, cloud-like. Written about observing someone else fall in love.", "style_prompt": "Warm intimate synth-pop ballad, 72 BPM, high frequencies rolled off for woolen softness, spacious cloud-like production, male vocal tender and breathy, no percussion until bridge, subtle bass pulse, analog warmth throughout, Juno synth pads sustained and blurring, third-person observational lyric, emotionally restrained tenderness, whispered harmonies layered under lead, feels like 3am quiet love, gentle and unhurried", "lyric_prompt": "Write a tender, slow pop ballad from a man's perspective — written in the third or second person, observing someone else fall in love. He's describing the small quiet signs that someone is in love. The emotional subtext is that HE is also in love — but this should never be stated outright, only felt. The language is extremely specific and sensory. No chorus in the traditional sense — the song flows as a series of observed moments. The title phrase appears only once, at the most devastating moment. Under 4 minutes."}, {"title": "All You Had to Do Was Stay", "album": "1989", "year": 2014, "bpm": 120, "vibe": "Controlled anger · rejection of a returning ex", "dna": "Opening with a high-pitched vocal sting. Propulsive mid-tempo synth-pop. Attitude-forward. The chorus is a single repeated accusation. Male version: finally turning down an ex who left.", "style_prompt": "Bright attitude-forward 80s synth-pop, 120 BPM, propulsive drum machine, crisp high-pitched synth accents, male vocal controlled and sardonic — righteous not angry, layered backing harmonies on chorus with wagging-finger energy, mid-tempo with forward momentum, no guitar, clean punchy production, restrained but pointed delivery, emotionally closed-off narrator turning down an ex, short declarative chorus built on a single accusation repeated", "lyric_prompt": "Write a controlled, attitude-forward pop song from a man who had his heart broken by someone who left — and now she wants to come back. He's not angry, he's simply done. The chorus is built on one repeated accusation phrase — the one simple thing she failed to do. The verses recall the specific things she did or didn't do. The tone is wry, righteous, a little cold. The bridge is the moment she explains herself and he simply doesn't care anymore. Under 3:20."}, {"title": "Is It Over Now?", "album": "1989 (Vault)", "year": 2023, "bpm": 120, "vibe": "Synthwave power ballad · obsessive post-breakup spiral", "dna": "Opens with a seagull-like vocal hook created by Moog Model D and Juno-6. Synthwave-influenced power ballad. Lyrical mode: obsessively cataloguing a former partner's new life.", "style_prompt": "Synthwave-influenced 80s synth-pop power ballad, Moog synthesizer atmospheric opening hook, Juno-6 synth bed, heavily reverb-soaked vocal and drums, echoing drum machine, 120 BPM, male vocal raw and obsessive, spiraling emotional energy, specific jealous imagery in lyrics, wide cinematic production, layered synth harmonics, melancholic but melodically strong, post-breakup obsession energy, coastal atmospheric feel", "lyric_prompt": "Write a synthwave-flavored pop power ballad from the perspective of a man who is obsessively monitoring his ex's new life from a distance. The central question of the chorus is whether it is truly over — delivered with the sting of already knowing the answer. The verses are loaded with specific, jealous, almost forensic detail. The bridge should be the moment he realizes his obsession says more about him than about her. Chorus should repeat the central question with increasing desperation. Under 3:45."}, {"title": "This Love", "album": "1989", "year": 2014, "bpm": 90, "vibe": "Hypnotic dream-pop · cyclical doomed love", "dna": "The only 1989 track Swift wrote entirely alone. Hypnotically sparse, ocean-like production. The lyrics are almost circular — love that comes back even after it's ended.", "style_prompt": "Hypnotic dream-pop, 90 BPM, sparse oceanic production where silence is instrumentation, male vocal deep in reverb and haze, minimal percussion — soft brush drums only, sustained synth tones blurring together, circular melodic motif, no guitar, ethereal and trance-like, lyrics built on wave and tide imagery, emotionally haunted rather than sad, cyclical song structure mirroring the lyrical theme, intimate and isolating", "lyric_prompt": "Write a hypnotic, sparse dream-pop song about a love that a man keeps returning to even after it ended — a cyclical, almost tidal feeling. The central metaphor should be water: waves, tides, things returning to shore. The lyrics should feel like they are circling the same feeling from different angles rather than building a linear narrative. There should be one devastating line buried somewhere in the middle that suddenly makes everything else click. Under 4 minutes. Quiet, haunting, unhurried."}, {"title": "Cruel Summer", "album": "Lover", "year": 2019, "bpm": 170, "vibe": "Synth-pop ecstasy · secret love · screamed bridge", "dna": "Arguably the peak of the Swift/Antonoff collaboration. 170 BPM, relentless energy, pre-chorus builds unbearable tension, chorus explodes. The bridge is a screamed confessional. The secret/forbidden love angle.", "style_prompt": "Euphoric synth-pop peak energy, 170 BPM, relentless pulsing synth arpeggio, tight punchy drum machine, male vocal rising with building pre-chorus tension, explosive singalong chorus, pulsing bass synth bed, screamed emotional bridge over minimal backing, summer haze atmosphere, secret forbidden love energy, layered harmonies on chorus, Antonoff-style layered reverb-soaked production, irresistible momentum throughout", "lyric_prompt": "Write a euphoric synth-pop song about a man in a secret summer fling — a relationship he can't officially admit to anyone but feels so intensely he can barely contain it. The song should be structured so the tension builds almost unbearably before the chorus explodes into release. The bridge must be the emotional peak: a screamed or belted confessional — something raw, specific, the kind of thing you'd only say when drunk and overwhelmed. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "Look What You Made Me Do", "album": "Reputation", "year": 2017, "bpm": 128, "vibe": "Revenge pop · identity death · villain-mode", "dna": "Modular synth, fuzzy guitars through EMI strips, live piano, 808 drum hits, trap percussion. The old version of the narrator is 'dead.' Maximalist, theatrical, dark.", "style_prompt": "Dark maximalist electropop revenge anthem, 128 BPM, modular synth riff, fuzzy distorted guitar stabs, live piano accents, heavy 808 bass hits, trap-influenced percussion, spoken word section, male vocal cold and theatrical — deadly calm not screaming, no warmth in production, hard-panned elements, cinematic villain energy, identity-death narrative arc, bombastic production with dramatic silence contrasts, dark and industrial atmosphere", "lyric_prompt": "Write a dark theatrical pop revenge anthem from a man announcing that the version of himself people knew and manipulated is gone. The tone is icy, theatrical, calculated — not a breakdown, a PERFORMANCE of vengeance. The chorus is a single accusation/threat delivered with absolute cold control. There should be a spoken-word section where he addresses his enemies directly. The bridge is the moment he announces the identity switch — the old him is explicitly pronounced dead. Under 3:30."}, {"title": "Getaway Car", "album": "Reputation", "year": 2017, "bpm": 156, "vibe": "Cinematic heist energy · doomed exciting love", "dna": "Breathless 156 BPM, cinematic action-movie production. Pure narrative momentum — a relationship told as a heist movie.", "style_prompt": "Breathless cinematic synth-pop, 156 BPM, driving pulsing synth bass, snapping drum machine, wide reverb on male vocal, action-movie heist energy, narrative velocity throughout, no slow moments — relentless forward momentum, layered backing harmonies, bright punchy production, doomed romance storytelling tone, Antonoff-style reverb-drenched mix, dramatic bridge with gear-shift, feels like a car chase through a city at night", "lyric_prompt": "Write a fast, cinematic pop song that tells a doomed love story using a heist or car chase as the extended metaphor. A man and a woman were bad for each other from the start — they both knew it — and chose to run anyway. The whole song should feel like a thriller. Use heist/getaway language organically woven into the emotional narrative. The last line should land like a body hitting the floor. Under 3:30. Pure momentum."}, {"title": "Gorgeous", "album": "Reputation", "year": 2017, "bpm": 100, "vibe": "Playful obsession · resentful attraction", "dna": "Mid-tempo, playful. Lighter production within Reputation's dark palette. The emotional core: someone being so attractive it makes you angry.", "style_prompt": "Playful mid-tempo electropop, 100 BPM, lighter production within dark Reputation palette, bouncy synth bed, warm drum machine, male vocal charming and self-deprecating — humor mixed with genuine attraction, childlike innocent opening before adult complexity, layered harmonies on chorus, conversational lyric delivery, resentful-attraction emotional core", "lyric_prompt": "Write a playful, self-aware pop song from a man who is genuinely furious at a woman for being so impossibly attractive that she has ruined his evening, his composure, and possibly his entire life. The tone is comedic on the surface but the attraction underneath is completely real. Include one line that's genuinely funny and one line that suddenly reveals the depth of his feeling. The bridge should be the moment the comedy drops and the real emotion surfaces briefly. Under 3:20."}, {"title": "This Is Why We Can't Have Nice Things", "album": "Reputation", "year": 2017, "bpm": 160, "vibe": "Gleeful revenge party · fake-out bridge laugh", "dna": "Roaring opening, celebratory chaos. Big brass-style synths, driving beat, a bridge that fakes sincerity before breaking into laughter. Pure gleeful revenge.", "style_prompt": "Gleeful celebratory electropop revenge anthem, 160 BPM, roaring brass-synth stab opening, driving party-energy beat, male vocal delighted and triumphant — not angry, openly gleeful, big singalong chorus with celebratory energy, fake-sincere bridge that breaks into laughter or sarcasm, wide arena production, punchy drums, revenge party atmosphere, Antonoff maximalist celebration mode", "lyric_prompt": "Write a gleeful, celebratory pop revenge song from a man who has been betrayed by a close friend or partner and is now publicly, joyfully celebrating the consequences. The tone is NOT angry — it's delighted. The bridge must include a fake-out: he begins with something that sounds sincere and heartfelt — and then the sarcasm kicks back in, harder. The last line should be the most devastating and funny line in the whole song. Under 3:15."}, {"title": "London Boy", "album": "Lover", "year": 2019, "bpm": 100, "vibe": "Besotted cultural tourism love song", "dna": "Joyful, light, filled with place names and cultural references. Acoustic and electronic hybrid. A love letter to both a person AND their city.", "style_prompt": "Joyful acoustic-electronic hybrid pop, 100 BPM, light acoustic guitar strumming over synth bed, bright production, male vocal warm and besotted — maximum enthusiasm, cultural place-name-dropping lyric style, singalong chorus built on geographic/cultural specificity, no darkness anywhere in the production, warm analog warmth, feels like writing a love letter to a city and a person simultaneously", "lyric_prompt": "Write a joyful, besotted pop song from a man who has fallen completely in love with a woman from another city or country — and by extension, completely fallen in love with her world: her city, her culture, her accent, the specific places she takes him. Lyrics should be packed with specific cultural and geographic references. The tone is infectious enthusiasm. No darkness, no conflict — this is a pure love song disguised as a travel itinerary. Under 3:15. Pure joy."}, {"t